{"title_page": "George Hamilton (actor)", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = George Hamilton\n| image = George Hamilton 1969.JPG\n| caption = Hamilton in a publicity photo, 1969\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1939|08|12|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Memphis, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| residence = [[Palm Beach, Florida]], U.S. <br> [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| birth_name = George Stevens Hamilton\n| years_active = 1952\u2013present\n| occupation = Actor\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Alana Stewart]]|1972|1975|reason=divorced}}\n| partner = Kimberly Blackford <small>(1997\u20131999)</small>\n| children = 2, including [[Ashley Hamilton]]\n| parents = [[George Hamilton (musician)|George Hamilton]]<br />Ann Stevens\n}}\n'''George Stevens Hamilton''' (born August 12, 1939) is an American [[film]] and [[television]] [[actor]]. His notable films include ''[[Home from the Hill (film)|Home from the Hill]]'' (1960), ''[[By Love Possessed (film)|By Love Possessed]]'' (1961), ''[[Light in the Piazza (film)|Light in the Piazza]]'' (1962), ''[[Your Cheatin' Heart (film)|Your Cheatin' Heart]]'' (1964), ''[[Once Is Not Enough (film)|Once Is Not Enough]]'' (1975), ''[[Love at First Bite]]'' (1979), ''[[Zorro, The Gay Blade]]'' (1981), ''[[The Godfather Part III]]'' (1990), ''[[Doc Hollywood]]'' (1991), ''[[8 Heads in a Duffel Bag]]'' (1997), ''[[Hollywood Ending]]'' (2002) and ''[[The Congressman]]'' (2016). For his debut performance in ''[[Crime and Punishment U.S.A.]]'' (1959), Hamilton won a [[Golden Globe Award]] and was nominated for a [[BAFTA Award]]. He has received one additional BAFTA nomination and two additional Golden Globe nominations.\n\nHamilton began his film career in 1958 and although he has a substantial body of work in film and television he is, perhaps, most famous for his debonair style and his perpetual suntan. [[Bo Derek]] writes in her autobiography that \"there was an ongoing contest between [[John Derek|John]] [Derek] and George Hamilton as to who was tanner\".<ref>Derek, Bo (with Mark Seal) (2002), ''Riding Lessons: Everything That Matters in Life I Learned from Horses'', ReganBooks HarperCollins, {{ISBN|0060394374}}, p.212</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHamilton was born in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], the middle of three boys with an older maternal half brother and a younger full brother, and lived in [[Blytheville, Arkansas]]. He is the eldest son of bandleader [[George Hamilton (musician)|George \"Spike\" Hamilton]].<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/43/George-Hamilton.html George Hamilton Biography (1939\u2013)<!-- Bot generated title -->] from filmreference.com</ref>\n\nHis stepfathers were Carleton Hunt and Jesse Spalding; his stepmother was June Howard, with whom Hamilton said he had an affair when he was 12 years old which was shortly after she married his father.<ref>Beifuss, John. [http://m.commercialappeal.com/news/2008/nov/04/from-blytheville/ \"From Blytheville to Hollywood, George Hamilton looks back in memoir.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208061034/http://m.commercialappeal.com/news/2008/nov/04/from-blytheville/ |date=December 8, 2008 }} ''Commercial Appeal''. November 4, 2008</ref>\n\nHamilton attended the [[Hackley School]] in [[Tarrytown, New York]], graduating in 1957.<ref name=\"PAGESIX\">Burroni, Christine, [https://pagesix.com/20George Hamilton reminisces about his high school days\"], ''pagesix.com'', October 21, 2017</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early appearances===\nHamilton's first roles were in TV. He appeared on such shows as ''[[The Veil (TV series)|The Veil]]'' (playing an Indian), ''[[The Adventures of Rin Tin Tin]]'', ''[[The Donna Reed Show]]'' and ''[[Cimarron City]]''.\n\nHis first film role was a lead, ''[[Crime and Punishment U.S.A.]]'' (1959), directed by [[Denis Sanders]]. Although shot in 1958 it was not released until the following year.\n\nHowever the film was seen by [[Vincente Minnelli]] who thought Hamilton would be ideal for the younger son in ''[[Home from the Hill (film)|Home from the Hill]]'' (1960), a Southern melodrama with [[Robert Mitchum]]. Hamilton was duly cast and the film was popular. [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] signed him to a long-term contract.\n\n===Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer===\nMGM cast Hamilton in support of [[Natalie Wood]] and [[Robert Wagner]] in the melodrama ''[[All the Fine Young Cannibals]]'' (1960) which flopped at the box office.\n\nHamilton's next film was far more popular, the beach party comedy ''[[Where the Boys Are]]'' (1960). This was a hit and remains one of his best known movies.\n\nHamilton wanted to do more serious material, however, so he appeared in the lower budgeted ''[[Angel Baby (1961 film)|Angel Baby]]'' (1961), a drama about an evangelist, for [[Allied Artists Pictures Corporation|Allied Artists]]. It had minimal commercial or critical impact. For [[United Artists]] he supported [[Lana Turner]] in a melodrama, ''[[By Love Possessed (film)|By Love Possessed]]'' (1961).\n\nMGM tried to change his image by putting him in a Western, ''[[A Thunder of Drums]]'' (1961) alongside [[Richard Boone]]; the film was mildly popular.\n\nHamilton lobbied hard for the role of the Italian husband in ''[[Light in the Piazza (film)|Light in the Piazza]]'' (1962), another melodrama, with [[Olivia de Havilland]]. The film lost money but Hamilton received excellent notices. It was shot in Italy, and MGM kept Hamilton in that country to play a role in ''[[Two Weeks in Another Town]]'' (1962), an unsuccessful attempt to repeat the success of ''[[The Bad and the Beautiful]]'' (1952).\n\nHamilton had an excellent part in ''[[The Victors (film)|The Victors]]'' (1963), an anti-war drama from [[Carl Foreman]]. It was a box office disappointment but was critically acclaimed. Hamilton had another good role in ''[[Act One (film)|Act One]]'' (1963), playing [[Moss Hart]], but the movie was poorly received. He guest starred on episodes of ''[[Bob Hope Presents the Chrysler Theatre]]'' and ''[[Burke's Law (1963 TV series)|Burke's Law]]''.\n\nAfter making a cameo in ''[[Looking for Love (film)|Looking for Love]]'' (1964), Hamilton appeared in another biopic, ''[[Your Cheatin' Heart (film)|Your Cheatin' Heart]]'' (1964), playing [[Hank Williams]]. The movie was not widely seen but had its fans and Hamilton's performance received some praise. He guest starred on episodes of ''[[The Rogues (TV series)|The Rogues]]'' and ''[[Ben Casey]]''.\n\nHamilton went to Mexico to support [[Jeanne Moreau]] and [[Brigitte Bardot]] in ''[[Viva Maria!]]'' (1965). It was directed by [[Louis Malle]] who cast Hamilton on the strength of his performance in ''[[Two Weeks in Another Town]]''. Malle said \"he was a personal choice and I am happy with him.... He's more interested in being in the social columns&nbsp;\u2013 I don't understand&nbsp;\u2013 when he should be one of the greatest of his generation.\"<ref>He Blunted U.S. Blue Pencil Thomas, Kevin. Los Angeles Times (June 29, 1965: C8</ref> The film was hugely popular in Europe, but did not break through to the US.\n\nHamilton made a movie in France, ''[[That Man George]]'' (1965) and appeared in a production of ''[[A Farewell to Arms (1966 film)|A Farewell to Arms]]'' (1966) on TV, opposite [[Vanessa Redgrave]].\n\nHe returned to MGM to make a romantic comedy with [[Sandra Dee]], ''[[Doctor, You've Got to Be Kidding!]]'' (1967), which was mildly popular. At Columbia he co-starred with [[Glenn Ford]] in a Western ''[[A Time for Killing]]'' (1967), originally directed by [[Roger Corman]] then [[Phil Karlson]].\n\nHamilton played a cat burglar in MGM's ''[[Jack of Diamonds (1967 film)|Jack of Diamonds]]'' (1967). It was produced by Sandy Howard who said Hamilton was \"a hot commodity these days\" because he was dating [[Lyndon Johnson]]'s daughter.<ref>Lynda Johnson Gets A Job at McCall's: LYNDA BIRD GETS A JOB AT M'CALL'S By TERENCE SMITH. New York Times (October 6, 1966: 1.</ref> Reports put his fee around this time at $100,000 a movie. He was drafted into the army but received a 3-A deferral notice on the grounds he was the sole financial provider for his mother.<ref>HAMILTON TELLS OF BUSY CAREER: But Sought-After Actor Is Silent on Role as Suitor By VINCENT CANBY. New York Times  October 7, 1966: 38.</ref> (Hamilton's draft deferment was highly controversial at the time because it was thought that his relationship with the president's daughter gave him preferential treatment.<ref>Carmichael Says He Won't Go if Drafted: CARMICHAEL VOWS HE WON'T SERVE By THOMAS A. JOHNSON. New York Times ] October 29, 1966: 1.</ref>)\n\nHamilton then made a science fiction movie for [[George Pal]] at MGM, ''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]'' (1968).\n\n===Television===\nGeorge went into television in 1969, supporting [[Lana Turner]] in the all-star ABC series ''[[Harold Robbins' The Survivors]]'' (1969\u201370).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-survivors/cast/204719/|title=The Survivors (1969) Cast| website=TVGuide.com|publisher=[[TV Guide]]|access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhen the show was canceled in January 1970, George went into ''[[Paris 7000]]'' (1970). He portrayed a trouble shooter for the US State Department in Paris helping US citizens. This series was canceled in March 1970.\n\nHe starred in the TV films ''[[Togetherness (film)|Togetherness]]'' (1970) and ''[[The Last of the Powerseekers]]'', a 1971 compilation of two episodes of ''[[Harold Robbins' The Survivors]]''.\n\n===Producer===\nHamilton decided to move into producing to give himself greater control over his career. He produced and played the title role in ''[[Evel Knievel (1971 film)|Evel Knievel]]'' (1971). Hamilton had the script rewritten by [[John Milius]] who later called Hamilton \"a wonderful guy, totally underrated. A great con-man, that's what he really is. He always said, 'I'll be remembered as a third-rate actor when in fact, I'm a first-rate con man'.\"<ref name=\"nat\">Segaloff, Nat, \"John Milius: The Good Fights\", ''Backstory 4: Interviews with Screenwriters of the 1970s and 1980s'', Ed. [[Patrick McGilligan (biographer)|Patrick McGilligan]], Uni of California 2006 p 289</ref>\n\nHe appeared in a TV movie, ''[[The Last of the Powerseekers]]'' (1973), and had a support role as a wealthy rancher whose wife was trying to leave him in the western, ''[[The Man Who Loved Cat Dancing (film)|The Man Who Loved Cat Dancing]]'', starring [[Burt Reynolds]] (1973).\n\nHe produced and appeared in ''[[Medusa (1973 film)|Medusa]]'' (1973). He starred in the TV movie ''[[The Dead Don't Die (1975 film)|The Dead Don't Die]]'' (1975) and had a support role in ''[[Once Is Not Enough]]'' (1975). On a 1975 episode of ''[[Columbo (TV series)|Columbo]]'', Hamilton played a psychiatrist who uses hypnosis to commit a murder, whose arrogant assertions in his own defence establish that he was in fact at the scene of the crime. \n\nHamilton guest starred on episodes of ''[[Police Story (1973 TV series)|Police Story]]'', ''[[McCloud (TV series)|McCloud]]'', ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'', ''[[The Eddie Capra Mysteries]]'', ''[[Gibbsville (TV series)|Gibbsville]]'', ''[[Supertrain]]'', and ''[[Sword of Justice]]''.\n\nHe had support roles in ''[[The Strange Possession of Mrs. Oliver]]'' (1977), ''[[The Happy Hooker Goes to Washington]]'' (1977), ''[[Killer on Board]]'' (1977), ''[[Sextette (film)|Sextette]]'' (1978), ''[[The Users (1978 film)|The Users]]'' (1978), ''[[From Hell to Victory]]'' (1979), ''[[Institute for Revenge]]'' (1979), ''[[From Hell to Victory]]'' (1979) and ''[[Death Car on the Freeway]]'' (1979).\n\n===''Love at First Bite''===\nA surprise blockbuster hit came his way in 1979 when Hamilton showed a flair for comedy in ''[[Love at First Bite]]'' which was the story of [[Count Dracula]]'s pursuit of a young Manhattanite model, played by [[Susan Saint James]]. The movie included such scenes as Dracula and his conquest dancing to \"[[I Love the Nightlife]]\" at a disco. The film's box-office success created a popularity surge for Hamilton, who also served as executive producer.\n\nHe returned to TV for ''[[The Seekers (miniseries)|The Seekers]]'' (1979) and ''[[The Great Cash Giveaway Getaway]]'' (1979) then he did a ''Love at First Bite'' style comedy, 1981's ''[[Zorro, the Gay Blade]]'', which he produced.\n\nHowever, ''Zorro'' was not as popular as ''Love at First Bite'' and film leads dried up quickly. He focused on television: ''[[Malibu (TV movie)|Malibu]]'' (1983) and ''[[Two Fathers' Justice]]'' (1985).\n\nIn the mid-1980s, Hamilton starred in the sixth season of the ABC [[Aaron Spelling]]-produced nighttime television serial ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]''.\n\nHe supported [[Joan Collins]] in the mini series ''[[Monte Carlo (miniseries)|Monte Carlo]]'' (1986) and had the lead in a short lived series ''[[Spies (TV series)|Spies]]'' (1987).  He supported [[Elizabeth Taylor]] in ''[[Poker Alice]]'' (1987).\n\n===1990s===\nA break for Hamilton came in 1990 when [[Francis Ford Coppola]] cast him as the Corleone family's lawyer in a much-anticipated film, ''[[The Godfather Part III]]''.\n\nFor the second time, he portrayed a murderer on the television series ''[[Columbo]]'', starring as the host of a TV true-crime show in the 1991 episode \"[[List of Columbo episodes|Caution: Murder Can Be Hazardous to Your Health]].\" He had previously been in the 1975 episode \"A Deadly State of Mind\".\n\nHamilton had small roles in ''[[Doc Hollywood]]'' (1992), ''[[Once Upon a Crime...]]'' (1992) and ''[[Amore! (film)|Amore]]'' (1993) and guest starred on ''[[Diagnosis Murder]]'' and ''[[Dream On (TV series)|Dream On]]''. He went to Germany to make ''[[Das Paradies am Ende der Berge]]'' (1993) and did ''[[Two Fathers: Justice for the Innocent]]'' (1994), ''[[Vanished]]'' (1995), and ''[[Playback (film)|Playback]]'' (1996), as well as guest starring on shows like ''Bonnie'', ''Diagnosis Murder'', ''Hart to Hart'' and ''The Guilt''.\n\nHe was in ''[[Meet Wally Sparks]]'' (1997), ''[[8 Heads in a Duffel Bag]]'' (1997), and ''[[Rough Riders (miniseries)|Rough Riders]]'' (1997). With his matinee-idol looks it was sometimes noted that Hamilton physically resembled [[Warren Beatty]]. Beatty's political satire ''[[Bulworth]]'' (1998) contained a running gag about this with Hamilton appearing as himself in a brief cameo. Hamilton had a regular role on the short lived TV series ''[[Jenny (TV series)|Jenny]]'' (1997).\n\nHe was in ''[[Casper Meets Wendy]]'' (1998), ''[[P.T. Barnum (film)|P.T. Barnum]]'' (1999) and ''[[She's Too Tall]]'' (1999). He was a semi-regular celebrity guest on the 1998-99 syndicated version of ''[[Match Game]]''\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2003, Hamilton hosted ''[[The Family (U.S. TV series)|The Family]]'' which was a reality television series on ABC for one season. The program starred ten members from a traditional Italian-American family, each fighting for a $1,000,000 prize. In 2006, Hamilton competed in the second season of ABC's ''Dancing with the Stars''<ref>[http://abc.go.com/primetime/dancing/ Dancing With The Stars]&nbsp;\u2013 ABC.com</ref> with professional [[Edyta Sliwinska]] in which they lasted until the sixth round. At age 66 and recovering from knee injuries, Hamilton, unable to match the limber dance moves of his younger competitors, charmed the audience and judges with endearingly silly dances utilizing props including a [[Zorro]] mask and the sword from ''Zorro, The Gay Blade''.\n\nIn 2006, it was rumored that Hamilton would replace [[Bob Barker]] on ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]''. He auditioned for the show and in March 2007, [[TMZ.com|TMZ]] reported that Hamilton was a frontrunner to replace Barker. According to [[Reuters]], Hamilton was one of the final three contenders to host the show, alongside [[Mark Steines]] and [[Todd Newton]].<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/televisionNews/idUSN1624240720070416 Trio remaining in Price line] from Reuters</ref> Soon thereafter, however, [[Drew Carey]] was named as Barker's successor. Subsequently, Hamilton has hosted the live stage adaptation of the show, ''[[The Price Is Right Live!]]''. In August 2008, Hamilton co-starred in ''Coma'', a web series on [[Crackle (company)|Crackle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Madsen, George Hamilton and Paul Ben-Victor Star in Coma, an Original Web Series Premiering On Crackle.com|url=http://www.webwire.com/ViewPressRel.asp?aId=73148|publisher=webwire.com|date=August 22, 2008|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> Hamilton was executive producer of the 2009 film ''[[My One and Only (film)|My One and Only]]'', which is loosely based on his early life and relationship with his mother.\n\nHamilton was honored with a star on the Hollywood Walk Of Fame on August 12, 2009&nbsp;\u2013 his 70th birthday.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.daylife.com/photo/0bMv0nZ2Ce94v |title=Content Marketing Platform - B2B and B2C Content Marketing Technology - NewsCred |publisher=Daylife.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304070010/http://www.daylife.com/photo/0bMv0nZ2Ce94v |archivedate=March 4, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 1999, a Golden Palm Star on the [[Palm Springs, California]], [[Palm Springs Walk of Stars|Walk of Stars]] was dedicated to him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180508121758/http://www.palmspringswalkofstars.com/web-storage/Stars/Stars+dedicated+by+date.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=May 8, 2018|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> Hamilton appeared as a contestant on the UK edition of ''[[I'm a Celebrity\u2026Get Me out of Here! (UK series 9)]]'' in November 2009. Hamilton walked out of the jungle on November 30, 2009, telling the other contestants that he wasn't there to win, but to have fun.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/celebrity/news/a189195/george-hamilton-quits-im-a-celebrity-prog.html|title=George Hamilton 'quits I'm A Celebrity'|author=Alex Fletcher|website=Digital Spy}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8386759.stm|work=BBC News|title=Hamilton leaves I'm a Celebrity|date=November 30, 2009|accessdate=May 3, 2010}}</ref> Hamilton was considered one of the favorites to win the series. In 2010 Hamilton was chosen as one of [[David Hasselhoff]]'s roasters in the ''[[Comedy Central Roast#David Hasselhoff|Comedy Central Roast of David Hasselhoff]]''. Starting in the fall of 2011, Hamilton starred as \"Georges\" for the national tour of the [[Tony Award|Tony]]-winning revival of ''[[La Cage aux Folles (musical)|La Cage aux Folles]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://broadwayworld.com/article/George-Hamilton-to-Star-in-National-Tour-of-LA-CAGE-AUX-FOLLES-20110425 |title=George Hamilton to Star in National Tour of LA CAGE AUX FOLLES |publisher=Broadwayworld.com}}</ref> He was still starring in the show {{as of|2012|June|lc=y}}.\n\nIn 2015 George and his ex-wife, Alana Hamilton appeared in Season 4/Episode 10 of Celebrity Wife Swap. Alana swapped with Angela \"Big Ang\" Raiola of Mob Wives fame, and her husband, Neil Murphy. In the summer of 2016, Hamilton appeared in television commercials for [[KFC]] as the \"Extra Crispy Colonel,\" a deeply tanned version of the company's mascot, [[Colonel Sanders]], a role which he returned to in the spring of 2018. In the summer of 2018, Hamilton will portray the Colonel on ''[[General Hospital]]''.<ref name=\"Rice\"/>\n\n==Business endeavors and misc==\nIn the late 1980s Hamilton launched the George Hamilton Skin Care System and the George Hamilton Sun Care System and tanning salons.<ref>{{cite book |title=Marketing Madness: A Survival Guide For A Consumer Society |last=Jacobson |first=Michael |last2=Masur |first2=Laurie |last3=Collins |first3=Ron |year=1995 |publisher=Westview Press |location= |isbn=978-0-8133-1980-3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/marketingmadness00jacorich/page/60 60] |pages= |url=https://archive.org/details/marketingmadness00jacorich |url-access=registration |accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Where the Sun Shines, There He Is |author=Alexander, Ron |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 19, 1989 |url= }}</ref> A cigar lounge bearing his name was opened in the late 1990s at the [[New York-New York Hotel and Casino|New York, New York, hotel]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]] and other locations, along with a line of cigars bearing the actor's name. A January 1998 article in ''Cigar Aficionado'' magazine described Hamilton's style as \"[[Cary Grant]] meets [[Pat Riley]]\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Benes |first1=Alejandro |last2= |first2= |year= |title=Hamiltons Las Vegas |journal=CigarAficionado |publisher=CigarAficionado |volume=Mar-Apr 1998 |issue= |pages= |url= |doi= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Minkoff |first1=Alysse |last2= |first2= |year= |title=Forever Suave|journal=CigarAficionado |publisher=CigarAficionado |volume=Jan-Feb 1998 |issue= |pages= |url= |doi= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=|first1= |last2= |first2= |year= |title=Smoke a Stogie|journal=Los Angeles Magazine |publisher= |volume=Oct 1999 |issue= |pages= |url= |doi= }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2006 Hamilton served as grand marshal for the 79th Annual [[Shenandoah Apple Blossom Festival]] in [[Winchester, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebloom.com/celebrities-past.html |title=Past Shenandoah Apple Blossom Festivals |accessdate=July 24, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716223202/http://www.thebloom.com/celebrities-past.html |archivedate=July 16, 2011 }}</ref> In 2016 and 2018, Hamilton appeared as the \"Crispy Colonel\" in commercials for [[KFC]], playing on his \"Tan Man\" image.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/george-hamilton-reprises-his-role-as-colonel-sanders-i-m-guy-who-has-parlayed-a-tan-a-career-1104003|title=George Hamilton Reprises His Role as Colonel Sanders: \"I'm the Only Guy Who Has Parlayed a Tan Into a Career\"|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1966 Hamilton had a relationship with [[Lynda Bird Johnson]], the daughter of US President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/reliable-source/post/lynda-johnson-robb-and-george-hamilton-when-a-presidents-daughter-dated-a-movie-star/2012/02/10/gIQAuXZO9Q_blog.html |title=Lynda Johnson Robb and George Hamilton: When a president\u2019s daughter dated a movie star |newspaper=Washington Post }}</ref> Hamilton was married to actress [[Alana Stewart]] from 1972 to 1975. Their son, [[Ashley Hamilton]], was born in 1974. George Thomas Hamilton is his younger son (born in December 1999) with his ex-girlfriend Kimberly Blackford.\n\nThe divorced Hamiltons reunited in the mid-1990s to co-host a daytime talk show, ''[[George and Alana]]''. In ''I'm A Celebrity'' he revealed he had dated at least four Miss Worlds. Hamilton has a well-known social relationship with [[Imelda Marcos]], the widow of former [[Philippines]] president [[Ferdinand Marcos]]. It was later revealed that he also had business ties to the Marcoses. In 1990 Hamilton was named as an unindicted co-conspirator in a federal fraud and racketeering case against the Marcoses involving looting Philippine government funds; Imelda was acquitted in the case.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-10-09/news/mn-2056_1_beverly-hills | first1=William C. | last1=Rempel | first2=Henry | last2=Weinstein | work=Los Angeles Times | date=October 9, 1990 | title=COLUMN ONE : An Actor's Close Ties to Marcos : The Philippine government's quest for missing funds leads to George Hamilton's former doorstep in Beverly Hills}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Burt Reynolds]]' autobiography,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Reynolds|first1=Burt |year=1994 |title=My Life |url=https://archive.org/details/mylifereyn00reyn|url-access=registration|publisher=Hyperion Books |ISBN=978-0-7868-6130-9 }}</ref> Hamilton has a healthy sense of humor, even when the humor is directed at him: Reynolds once made up a [[birthday card]] for Hamilton with a composite photograph of [[Tony Curtis]] and [[Anthony Perkins]], titled \"To George, love from Mum and Dad\". Hamilton found the card hilarious and showed it to everybody. ''[[My One and Only (film)|My One and Only]]'', a 2009 comedy film starring Logan Lerman, was loosely based on a story about George Hamilton's early life on the road with his mother and brother, featuring anecdotes that Hamilton had told to [[Merv Griffin]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Lone Star (1952 film)|Lone Star]]'' (1952) as Noah (uncredited)\n* ''[[Crime and Punishment U.S.A.]]'' (1959) as Robert\n* ''[[Home from the Hill (film)|Home from the Hill]]'' (1960) as Theron Hunnicutt\n* ''[[All the Fine Young Cannibals]]'' (1960) as Tony McDowall\n* ''[[Where the Boys Are]]'' (1960) as Ryder Smith\n* ''[[Angel Baby (1961 film)|Angel Baby]]'' (1961) as Paul Strand\n* ''[[By Love Possessed (film)|By Love Possessed]]'' (1961) as Warren Winner\n* ''[[A Thunder of Drums]]'' (1961) as Lt. Curtis McQuade\n* ''[[Light in the Piazza (film)|The Light in the Piazza]]'' (1962) as Fabrizio Naccarelli\n* ''[[Two Weeks in Another Town]]'' (1962) as Davie Drew\n* ''[[The Victors (film)|The Victors]]'' (1963) as Cpl. Theodore Trower\n* ''[[Act One (film)|Act One]]'' (1963) as Moss Hart\n* ''[[Looking for Love (film)|Looking for Love]]'' (1964) as Himself (Cameo)\n* ''[[Your Cheatin' Heart (film)|Your Cheatin' Heart]]'' (1964) as Hank Williams\n* ''[[Viva Maria!]]'' (1965) as Flores\n* ''[[That Man George]]'' (1966) as George\n* ''[[Doctor, You've Got to Be Kidding!]]'' (1967) as Harlan Wycliff\n* ''[[A Time for Killing]]'' (1967) as Capt. Dorrit Bentley\n* ''[[Jack of Diamonds (1967 film)|Jack of Diamonds]]'' (1967) as Jeff Hill\n* ''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]'' (1968) as Prof. Jim Tanner\n* ''Togetherness'' (1970) as Jack DuPont\n* ''[[Elvis: That's the Way It Is]]'' (1970) (documentary)\n* ''[[Evel Knievel (1971 film)|Evel Knievel]]'' (1971) as Evel Knievel\n* ''[[The Man Who Loved Cat Dancing (film)|The Man Who Loved Cat Dancing]]'' (1973) as Willard Crocker\n* ''[[Medusa (1973 film)|Medusa]]'' (1973) as Jeffrey\n* ''[[Jacqueline Susann's Once Is Not Enough (film)|Once Is Not Enough]]'' (1975) as David Milford\n* ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'' (TV series/film) (1977)\n* ''[[The Happy Hooker Goes to Washington]]'' (1977) as Ward Thompson\n* ''The Magnificent Hustle'' (1978) as Donald Hightower\n* ''[[Sextette]]'' (1978) as Vance Norton\n* ''[[The Users (film)|The Users]]'' (1978) as Adam Baker\n* ''[[From Hell to Victory]]'' (1979) as Maurice Bernard\n* ''[[Love at First Bite]]'' (1979) as Count Vladimir Dracula\n* ''[[Death Car on the Freeway]]'' (1979) as Ray Jeffries\n* ''[[Zorro, The Gay Blade]]'' (1981) as Zorro The Gay Blade / Don Diego Vega / Bunny Wigglesworth\n* ''[[Malibu (film)|Malibu]]'' (1983) as Jay Pomerantz\n* ''[[Poker Alice (film)|Poker Alice]]'' (1987) as Cousin John Moffit\n* ''[[The Godfather Part III]]'' (1990) as B. J. Harrison\n* ''[[List of Columbo episodes#Season 10 and specials|Columbo: Caution: Murder can be Hazardous to your Health]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Doc Hollywood]]'' (1991) as Doctor Halberstrom\n* ''[[Once Upon a Crime]]'' (1992) as Alfonso de la Pena\n* ''[[Amore! (1993 film)|Amore!]]'' (1993) as Rudolpho Carbonera\n* ''[[Double Dragon (film)|Double Dragon]]'' (1994) as Channel 102 News Anchor (uncredited)\n* ''[[Vanished (1995 film)|Vanished]]'' (1995 TV movie) as Malcolm Patterson\n* ''Playback'' (1996) as Gil Braman\n* ''[[Meet Wally Sparks]]'' (1997) as Himself\n* ''[[8 Heads in a Duffel Bag]]'' (1997) as Dick Bennett\n* ''[[Bulworth]]'' (1998) as Himself (cameo) (uncredited)\n* ''[[Casper Meets Wendy]]'' (1998) as Desmond Spellman\n* ''She's Too Tall'' (1999) as Alonso Palermo\n* ''[[Off Key]]'' (2001) as Armand\n* ''[[Crocodile Dundee in Los Angeles]]'' (2001) as Himself (cameo)\n* ''Reflections of Evil'' (2002) as Duncan Carlyle\n* ''[[Hollywood Ending]]'' (2002) as Ed\n* ''Pets'' (1999) as Von Steiger ('The Hand')\n* ''The Little Unicorn'' (2002)\n* ''A Very Cool Christmas'' / Too Cool For Christmas'' (2004) as Santa Claus\n* ''[[The L.A. Riot Spectacular]]'' (2005) as The King of Beverly Hills\n* ''[[Rumor Has It (film)|Rumor Has It...]]'' (2005) as Himself (cameo) (uncredited)\n* ''Melvin Smarty'' (2012) as Hitman / Mexican Colonel\n* ''[[Rosemary Rodriguez|Silver Skies]]'' (2016) as Phil\n* ''[[The Congressman]]'' (2016) as Laird Devereaux\n* ''[[Swiped]]'' (2018) as Phil Singer\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Television work==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[The Donna Reed Show]]'' (as Herbie Shields in \"Have Fun\", 1959) as Herbie Shields\n* ''The Rogues'' (one episode  as Jamie, 1964) as Jamie\n* ''A Farewell to Arms'' (1966) (miniseries) as Lt. Frederick Henry\n* ''[[Harold Robbins' The Survivors]]'' (1969) as Duncan Carlyle\n* ''Paris 7000'' (1970) (canceled after 10 episodes) as Jack Brennan\n* ''The Last of the Powerseekers'' (1971) as Duncan Carlyle\n* ''[[The Dead Don't Die (1975 film)|The Dead Don't Die]]'' (1975) as Don Drake\n* ''[[List of Columbo episodes#Season 4|Columbo: A Deadly State of Mind]]'' (1975) as Dr Marcus Collier\n* ''Roots'' (1977) (miniseries) as Stephen Bennett\n* ''McCloud: The Great Taxicab Stampede'' (1977) as Keith Hampton\n* ''The Strange Possession of Mrs. Oliver'' (1977) as Greg Oliver\n* ''Killer on Board'' (1977) as Glenn Lyle\n* ''[[The Users (film)|The Users]]'' (1978) as Adam Baker\n* ''[[The Eddie Capra Mysteries]]'' (1978&nbsp;\u2013 Episode: \"Nightmare at Pendragon Castle\")\n* ''[[The Seekers (1979 film)|The Seekers]]'' (1979) as Lt. Hamilton Stovall\n* ''Institute for Revenge'' (1979) as Alan Roberto\n* ''Express to Terror'' (1979) (pilot for Supertrain) as David Belnik\n* ''[[Death Car on the Freeway]]'' (1979) as Ray Jeffries\n* ''The Great Cash Giveaway Getaway'' (1980) as Hightower\n* ''[[The Fantastic Miss Piggy Show]]'' (1982, TV Special) as himself\n* ''[[Malibu (film)|Malibu]]'' (1983) (miniseries) as Jay Pomerantz\n* ''[[Two Fathers' Justice]]'' (1985) as Trent Bradley\n* ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]'' (cast member from 1985\u20131986) as [[Joel Abrigore]]\n* ''[[Monte Carlo (miniseries)|Monte Carlo]]'' (1986) (miniseries) as Harry Price\n* ''[[Spies (TV series)|Spies]]'' (1987) as Ian Stone\n* ''Poker Alice'' (1987, based on the frontier gambler [[Poker Alice]]) as Cousin John Moffit\n* ''[[List of Columbo episodes#Season 10 and specials|Columbo: Caution: Murder Can Be Hazardous to Your Health]]'' (1991) as Wade Anders\n* ''The House on Sycamore Street'' (1992) as J.D. Gantry / Harry Lennox\n* ''[[List of Birds of a Feather episodes#Series 5|Birds of a Feather: It Happened in Hollywood]]'' (1993) as Himself\n* ''Das Paradies am Ende der Berge'' (1993) as Earl Henry von Hohenlodern\n* ''[[Two Fathers: Justice for the Innocent]]'' (1994) as Bradley\n* ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[George & Alana]]'' (1995\u20131996)\n* ''Vanished'' (1995) as Malcolm Patterson\n* ''The Guilt'' (1996) as Alan Van Buren\n* ''[[Hart to Hart]]'': Till Death Do Us Hart (1996) as Karl Von Ostenberg\n* ''[[Rough Riders (miniseries)|Rough Riders]]'' (1997) as [[William Randolph Hearst]]\n* ''[[Miss USA]]'' & ''[[Miss Universe]]'' (1997) as Host\n* ''[[Jenny (TV series)|Jenny]]'' (1997\u20131998) as Guy Hathaway\n* ''[[Casper Meets Wendy]]'' (1998) as Desmond Spellman\n* ''[[Baywatch]]'' (1 episode: season 9, episode 21) (1999) as Earl / Himself\n* ''P.T. Barnum'' (1999) as Francis Olmsted\n* ''The Family'' (2003) as Host\n* ''[[Las Vegas (TV series)|Las Vegas]]'' (guest appearance 2004) as Bernard Taylor\n* ''Too Cool for Christmas'' (2004) as Santa Claus\n* ''[[Joey (TV series)|Joey]]'' (guest appearance 2005)\n* ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]'' (cast member in 2006)\n* ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK series 9)|I'm A Celebrity Get Me Out Of Here!]]'' (2009) as Himself\n* ''The Comedy Central Roast Of David Hasselhoff'' (2010) as Himself&nbsp;\u2013 Roaster\n* ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]'' (2013) as Robin\n* ''[[Stewarts & Hamiltons]]'' (8 episodes, 2015) as Himself\n* ''[[Wife Swap (U.S. TV series)|Celebrity Wife Swap]]'' (1 episode, 2015) as Himself\n* ''[[2 Broke Girls]]'' (1 episode as Bob, 2016) as Bob\n* ''[[American Housewife]]'' (recurring, 2017\u20132019) as Spencer Blitz<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/09/07/george-hamilton-american-housewife-season-2/ |title=George Hamilton joins season 2 of American Housewife |last=Holub |first=Christian |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=September 7, 2017 |accessdate=September 9, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''[[General Hospital]]'' (July 6, 2018) as [[Colonel Sanders]]<ref name=\"Rice\">{{cite magazine|url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/07/04/general-hospital-george-hamilton-colonel-sanders/|title=General Hospital: See how George Hamilton will show up as Colonel Sanders|first=Lynette|last=Rice|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=[[New York City]]|date=July 4, 2018|accessdate=June 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''[[Grace and Frankie]]'' (1 episode, 2019) as Jack Patterson\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Books==\n* ''Life's Little Pleasures'' (co-authored with [[Alysse Minkoff]]) (1998)  {{ISBN|978-1575440866}}\n* ''Don't Mind If I Do or do I'' (co-authored with William Stadiem) (2009) {{ISBN|978-1416545071}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|1313|George Hamilton}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* [http://encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?entryID=6441 Encyclopedia of Arkansas History & Culture]\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for George Hamilton\n| list =\n{{Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year Actor}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Actor}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamilton, George}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:New Star of the Year (Actor) Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:MGM Records artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer contract players]]\n[[Category:Hackley School alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = George Hamilton\n| image = George Hamilton 1969.JPG\n| caption = Hamilton in a publicity photo, 1969\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1939|08|12|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Memphis, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| residence = [[Palm Beach, Florida]], U.S. <br> [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| birth_name = George Stevens Hamilton\n| years_active = 1952\u2013present\n| occupation = Actor\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Alana Stewart]]|1972|1975|reason=divorced}}\n| partner = Kimberly Blackford <small>(1997\u20131999)</small>\n| children = 2, including [[Ashley Hamilton]]\n| parents = [[George Hamilton (musician)|George Hamilton]]<br />Ann Stevens\n}}\n'''George Stevens Hamilton''' (born August 12, 1939) is an American [[film]] and [[television]] [[actor]]. His notable films include ''[[Home from the Hill (film)|Home from the Hill]]'' (1960), ''[[By Love Possessed (film)|By Love Possessed]]'' (1961), ''[[Light in the Piazza (film)|Light in the Piazza]]'' (1962), ''[[Your Cheatin' Heart (film)|Your Cheatin' Heart]]'' (1964), ''[[Once Is Not Enough (film)|Once Is Not Enough]]'' (1975), ''[[Love at First Bite]]'' (1979), ''[[Zorro, The Gay Blade]]'' (1981), ''[[The Godfather Part III]]'' (1990), ''[[Doc Hollywood]]'' (1991), ''[[8 Heads in a Duffel Bag]]'' (1997), ''[[Hollywood Ending]]'' (2002) and ''[[The Congressman]]'' (2016). For his debut performance in ''[[Crime and Punishment U.S.A.]]'' (1959), Hamilton won a [[Golden Globe Award]] and was nominated for a [[BAFTA Award]]. He has received one additional BAFTA nomination and two additional Golden Globe nominations.\n\nHamilton began his film career in 1958 and although he has a substantial body of work in film and television he is, perhaps, most famous for his debonair style and his perpetual suntan. [[Bo Derek]] writes in her autobiography that \"there was an ongoing contest between [[John Derek|John]] [Derek] and George Hamilton as to who was tanner\".<ref>Derek, Bo (with Mark Seal) (2002), ''Riding Lessons: Everything That Matters in Life I Learned from Horses'', ReganBooks HarperCollins, {{ISBN|0060394374}}, p.212</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHamilton was born in [[Memphis, Tennessee]], the middle of three boys with an older maternal half brother and a younger full brother, and lived in [[Blytheville, Arkansas]]. He is the eldest son of bandleader [[George Hamilton (musician)|George \"Spike\" Hamilton]].<ref>[http://www.filmreference.com/film/43/George-Hamilton.html George Hamilton Biography (1939\u2013)<!-- Bot generated title -->] from filmreference.com</ref>\n\nHis stepfathers were Carleton Hunt and Jesse Spalding; his stepmother was June Howard, with whom Hamilton said he had an affair when he was 12 years old which was shortly after she married his father.<ref>Beifuss, John. [http://m.commercialappeal.com/news/2008/nov/04/from-blytheville/ \"From Blytheville to Hollywood, George Hamilton looks back in memoir.\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081208061034/http://m.commercialappeal.com/news/2008/nov/04/from-blytheville/ |date=December 8, 2008 }} ''Commercial Appeal''. November 4, 2008</ref>\n\nHamilton attended the [[Hackley School]] in [[Tarrytown, New York]], graduating in 1957.<ref name=\"PAGESIX\">Burroni, Christine, [https://pagesix.com/20George Hamilton reminisces about his high school days\"], ''pagesix.com'', October 21, 2017</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Early appearances===\nHamilton's first roles were in TV. He appeared on such shows as ''[[The Veil (TV series)|The Veil]]'' (playing an Indian), ''[[The Adventures of Rin Tin Tin]]'', ''[[The Donna Reed Show]]'' and ''[[Cimarron City]]''.\n\nHis first film role was a lead, ''[[Crime and Punishment U.S.A.]]'' (1959), directed by [[Denis Sanders]]. Although shot in 1958 it was not released until the following year.\n\nHowever the film was seen by [[Vincente Minnelli]] who thought Hamilton would be ideal for the younger son in ''[[Home from the Hill (film)|Home from the Hill]]'' (1960), a Southern melodrama with [[Robert Mitchum]]. Hamilton was duly cast and the film was popular. [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] signed him to a long-term contract.\n\n===Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer===\nMGM cast Hamilton in support of [[Natalie Wood]] and [[Robert Wagner]] in the melodrama ''[[All the Fine Young Cannibals]]'' (1960) which flopped at the box office.\n\nHamilton's next film was far more popular, the beach party comedy ''[[Where the Boys Are]]'' (1960). This was a hit and remains one of his best known movies.\n\nHamilton wanted to do more serious material, however, so he appeared in the lower budgeted ''[[Angel Baby (1961 film)|Angel Baby]]'' (1961), a drama about an evangelist, for [[Allied Artists Pictures Corporation|Allied Artists]]. It had minimal commercial or critical impact. For [[United Artists]] he supported [[Lana Turner]] in a melodrama, ''[[By Love Possessed (film)|By Love Possessed]]'' (1961).\n\nMGM tried to change his image by putting him in a Western, ''[[A Thunder of Drums]]'' (1961) alongside [[Richard Boone]]; the film was mildly popular.\n\nHamilton lobbied hard for the role of the Italian husband in ''[[Light in the Piazza (film)|Light in the Piazza]]'' (1962), another melodrama, with [[Olivia de Havilland]]. The film lost money but Hamilton received excellent notices. It was shot in Italy, and MGM kept Hamilton in that country to play a role in ''[[Two Weeks in Another Town]]'' (1962), an unsuccessful attempt to repeat the success of ''[[The Bad and the Beautiful]]'' (1952).\n\nHamilton had an excellent part in ''[[The Victors (film)|The Victors]]'' (1963), an anti-war drama from [[Carl Foreman]]. It was a box office disappointment but was critically acclaimed. Hamilton had another good role in ''[[Act One (film)|Act One]]'' (1963), playing [[Moss Hart]], but the movie was poorly received. He guest starred on episodes of ''[[Bob Hope Presents the Chrysler Theatre]]'' and ''[[Burke's Law (1963 TV series)|Burke's Law]]''.\n\nAfter making a cameo in ''[[Looking for Love (film)|Looking for Love]]'' (1964), Hamilton appeared in another biopic, ''[[Your Cheatin' Heart (film)|Your Cheatin' Heart]]'' (1964), playing [[Hank Williams]]. The movie was not widely seen but had its fans and Hamilton's performance received some praise. He guest starred on episodes of ''[[The Rogues (TV series)|The Rogues]]'' and ''[[Ben Casey]]''.\n\nHamilton went to Mexico to support [[Jeanne Moreau]] and [[Brigitte Bardot]] in ''[[Viva Maria!]]'' (1965). It was directed by [[Louis Malle]] who cast Hamilton on the strength of his performance in ''[[Two Weeks in Another Town]]''. Malle said \"he was a personal choice and I am happy with him.... He's more interested in being in the social columns&nbsp;\u2013 I don't understand&nbsp;\u2013 when he should be one of the greatest of his generation.\"<ref>He Blunted U.S. Blue Pencil Thomas, Kevin. Los Angeles Times (June 29, 1965: C8</ref> The film was hugely popular in Europe, but did not break through to the US.\n\nHamilton made a movie in France, ''[[That Man George]]'' (1965) and appeared in a production of ''[[A Farewell to Arms (1966 film)|A Farewell to Arms]]'' (1966) on TV, opposite [[Vanessa Redgrave]].\n\nHe returned to MGM to make a romantic comedy with [[Sandra Dee]], ''[[Doctor, You've Got to Be Kidding!]]'' (1967), which was mildly popular. At Columbia he co-starred with [[Glenn Ford]] in a Western ''[[A Time for Killing]]'' (1967), originally directed by [[Roger Corman]] then [[Phil Karlson]].\n\nHamilton played a cat burglar in MGM's ''[[Jack of Diamonds (1967 film)|Jack of Diamonds]]'' (1967). It was produced by Sandy Howard who said Hamilton was \"a hot commodity these days\" because he was dating [[Lyndon Johnson]]'s daughter.<ref>Lynda Johnson Gets A Job at McCall's: LYNDA BIRD GETS A JOB AT M'CALL'S By TERENCE SMITH. New York Times (October 6, 1966: 1.</ref> Reports put his fee around this time at $100,000 a movie. He was drafted into the army but received a 3-A deferral notice on the grounds he was the sole financial provider for his mother.<ref>HAMILTON TELLS OF BUSY CAREER: But Sought-After Actor Is Silent on Role as Suitor By VINCENT CANBY. New York Times  October 7, 1966: 38.</ref> (Hamilton's draft deferment was highly controversial at the time because it was thought that his relationship with the president's daughter gave him preferential treatment.<ref>Carmichael Says He Won't Go if Drafted: CARMICHAEL VOWS HE WON'T SERVE By THOMAS A. JOHNSON. New York Times ] October 29, 1966: 1.</ref>)\n\nHamilton then made a science fiction movie for [[George Pal]] at MGM, ''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]'' (1968).\n\n===Television===\nGeorge went into television in 1969, supporting [[Lana Turner]] in the all-star ABC series ''[[Harold Robbins' The Survivors]]'' (1969\u201370).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-survivors/cast/204719/|title=The Survivors (1969) Cast| website=TVGuide.com|publisher=[[TV Guide]]|access-date=September 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nWhen the show was canceled in January 1970, George went into ''[[Paris 7000]]'' (1970). He portrayed a trouble shooter for the US State Department in Paris helping US citizens. This series was canceled in March 1970.\n\nHe starred in the TV films ''[[Togetherness (film)|Togetherness]]'' (1970) and ''[[The Last of the Powerseekers]]'', a 1971 compilation of two episodes of ''[[Harold Robbins' The Survivors]]''.\n\n===Producer===\nHamilton decided to move into producing to give himself greater control over his career. He produced and played the title role in ''[[Evel Knievel (1971 film)|Evel Knievel]]'' (1971). Hamilton had the script rewritten by [[John Milius]] who later called Hamilton \"a wonderful guy, totally underrated. A great con-man, that's what he really is. He always said, 'I'll be remembered as a third-rate actor when in fact, I'm a first-rate con man'.\"<ref name=\"nat\">Segaloff, Nat, \"John Milius: The Good Fights\", ''Backstory 4: Interviews with Screenwriters of the 1970s and 1980s'', Ed. [[Patrick McGilligan (biographer)|Patrick McGilligan]], Uni of California 2006 p 289</ref>\n\nHe appeared in a TV movie, ''[[The Last of the Powerseekers]]'' (1973), and had a support role as a wealthy rancher whose wife was trying to leave him in the western, ''[[The Man Who Loved Cat Dancing (film)|The Man Who Loved Cat Dancing]]'', starring [[Burt Reynolds]] (1973).\n\nHe produced and appeared in ''[[Medusa (1973 film)|Medusa]]'' (1973). He starred in the TV movie ''[[The Dead Don't Die (1975 film)|The Dead Don't Die]]'' (1975) and had a support role in ''[[Once Is Not Enough]]'' (1975). On a 1975 episode of ''[[Columbo (TV series)|Columbo]]'', Hamilton played a psychiatrist who uses hypnosis to commit a murder, whose arrogant assertions in his own defence establish that he was in fact at the scene of the crime. \n\nHamilton guest starred on episodes of ''[[Police Story (1973 TV series)|Police Story]]'', ''[[McCloud (TV series)|McCloud]]'', ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'', ''[[The Eddie Capra Mysteries]]'', ''[[Gibbsville (TV series)|Gibbsville]]'', ''[[Supertrain]]'', and ''[[Sword of Justice]]''.\n\nHe had support roles in ''[[The Strange Possession of Mrs. Oliver]]'' (1977), ''[[The Happy Hooker Goes to Washington]]'' (1977), ''[[Killer on Board]]'' (1977), ''[[Sextette (film)|Sextette]]'' (1978), ''[[The Users (1978 film)|The Users]]'' (1978), ''[[From Hell to Victory]]'' (1979), ''[[Institute for Revenge]]'' (1979), ''[[From Hell to Victory]]'' (1979) and ''[[Death Car on the Freeway]]'' (1979).\n\n===''Love at First Bite''===\nA surprise blockbuster hit came his way in 1979 when Hamilton showed a flair for comedy in ''[[Love at First Bite]]'' which was the story of [[Count Dracula]]'s pursuit of a young Manhattanite model, played by [[Susan Saint James]]. The movie included such scenes as Dracula and his conquest dancing to \"[[I Love the Nightlife]]\" at a disco. The film's box-office success created a popularity surge for Hamilton, who also served as executive producer.\n\nHe returned to TV for ''[[The Seekers (miniseries)|The Seekers]]'' (1979) and ''[[The Great Cash Giveaway Getaway]]'' (1979) then he did a ''Love at First Bite'' style comedy, 1981's ''[[Zorro, the Gay Blade]]'', which he produced.\n\nHowever, ''Zorro'' was not as popular as ''Love at First Bite'' and film leads dried up quickly. He focused on television: ''[[Malibu (TV movie)|Malibu]]'' (1983) and ''[[Two Fathers' Justice]]'' (1985).\n\nIn the mid-1980s, Hamilton starred in the sixth season of the ABC [[Aaron Spelling]]-produced nighttime television serial ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]''.\n\nHe supported [[Joan Collins]] in the mini series ''[[Monte Carlo (miniseries)|Monte Carlo]]'' (1986) and had the lead in a short lived series ''[[Spies (TV series)|Spies]]'' (1987).  He supported [[Elizabeth Taylor]] in ''[[Poker Alice]]'' (1987).\n\n===1990s===\nA break for Hamilton came in 1990 when [[Francis Ford Coppola]] cast him as the Corleone family's lawyer in a much-anticipated film, ''[[The Godfather Part III]]''.\n\nFor the second time, he portrayed a murderer on the television series ''[[Columbo]]'', starring as the host of a TV true-crime show in the 1991 episode \"[[List of Columbo episodes|Caution: Murder Can Be Hazardous to Your Health]].\" He had previously been in the 1975 episode \"A Deadly State of Mind\".\n\nHamilton had small roles in ''[[Doc Hollywood]]'' (1992), ''[[Once Upon a Crime...]]'' (1992) and ''[[Amore! (film)|Amore]]'' (1993) and guest starred on ''[[Diagnosis Murder]]'' and ''[[Dream On (TV series)|Dream On]]''. He went to Germany to make ''[[Das Paradies am Ende der Berge]]'' (1993) and did ''[[Two Fathers: Justice for the Innocent]]'' (1994), ''[[Vanished]]'' (1995), and ''[[Playback (film)|Playback]]'' (1996), as well as guest starring on shows like ''Bonnie'', ''Diagnosis Murder'', ''Hart to Hart'' and ''The Guilt''.\n\nHe was in ''[[Meet Wally Sparks]]'' (1997), ''[[8 Heads in a Duffel Bag]]'' (1997), and ''[[Rough Riders (miniseries)|Rough Riders]]'' (1997). With his matinee-idol looks it was sometimes noted that Hamilton physically resembled [[Warren Beatty]]. Beatty's political satire ''[[Bulworth]]'' (1998) contained a running gag about this with Hamilton appearing as himself in a brief cameo. Hamilton had a regular role on the short lived TV series ''[[Jenny (TV series)|Jenny]]'' (1997).\n\nHe was in ''[[Casper Meets Wendy]]'' (1998), ''[[P.T. Barnum (film)|P.T. Barnum]]'' (1999) and ''[[She's Too Tall]]'' (1999). He was a semi-regular celebrity guest on the 1998-99 syndicated version of ''[[Match Game]]''\n\n===2000s===\nIn 2003, Hamilton hosted ''[[The Family (U.S. TV series)|The Family]]'' which was a reality television series on ABC for one season. The program starred ten members from a traditional Italian-American family, each fighting for a $1,000,000 prize. In 2006, Hamilton competed in the second season of ABC's ''Dancing with the Stars''<ref>[http://abc.go.com/primetime/dancing/ Dancing With The Stars]&nbsp;\u2013 ABC.com</ref> with professional [[Edyta Sliwinska]] in which they lasted until the sixth round. At age 66 and recovering from knee injuries, Hamilton, unable to match the limber dance moves of his younger competitors, charmed the audience and judges with endearingly silly dances utilizing props including a [[Zorro]] mask and the sword from ''Zorro, The Gay Blade''.\n\nIn 2006, it was rumored that Hamilton would replace [[Bob Barker]] on ''[[The Price Is Right (U.S. game show)|The Price Is Right]]''. He auditioned for the show and in March 2007, [[TMZ.com|TMZ]] reported that Hamilton was a frontrunner to replace Barker. According to [[Reuters]], Hamilton was one of the final three contenders to host the show, alongside [[Mark Steines]] and [[Todd Newton]].<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/televisionNews/idUSN1624240720070416 Trio remaining in Price line] from Reuters</ref> Soon thereafter, however, [[Drew Carey]] was named as Barker's successor. Subsequently, Hamilton has hosted the live stage adaptation of the show, ''[[The Price Is Right Live!]]''. In August 2008, Hamilton co-starred in ''Coma'', a web series on [[Crackle (company)|Crackle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Madsen, George Hamilton and Paul Ben-Victor Star in Coma, an Original Web Series Premiering On Crackle.com|url=http://www.webwire.com/ViewPressRel.asp?aId=73148|publisher=webwire.com|date=August 22, 2008|accessdate=March 5, 2009}}</ref> Hamilton was executive producer of the 2009 film ''[[My One and Only (film)|My One and Only]]'', which is loosely based on his early life and relationship with his mother.\n\nHamilton was honored with a star on the Hollywood Walk Of Fame on August 12, 2009&nbsp;\u2013 his 70th birthday.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.daylife.com/photo/0bMv0nZ2Ce94v |title=Content Marketing Platform - B2B and B2C Content Marketing Technology - NewsCred |publisher=Daylife.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120304070010/http://www.daylife.com/photo/0bMv0nZ2Ce94v |archivedate=March 4, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 1999, a Golden Palm Star on the [[Palm Springs, California]], [[Palm Springs Walk of Stars|Walk of Stars]] was dedicated to him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180508121758/http://www.palmspringswalkofstars.com/web-storage/Stars/Stars+dedicated+by+date.pdf|title=Wayback Machine|date=May 8, 2018|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> Hamilton appeared as a contestant on the UK edition of ''[[I'm a Celebrity\u2026Get Me out of Here! (UK series 9)]]'' in November 2009. Hamilton walked out of the jungle on November 30, 2009, telling the other contestants that he wasn't there to win, but to have fun.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/celebrity/news/a189195/george-hamilton-quits-im-a-celebrity-prog.html|title=George Hamilton 'quits I'm A Celebrity'|author=Alex Fletcher|website=Digital Spy}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8386759.stm|work=BBC News|title=Hamilton leaves I'm a Celebrity|date=November 30, 2009|accessdate=May 3, 2010}}</ref> Hamilton was considered one of the favorites to win the series. In 2010 Hamilton was chosen as one of [[David Hasselhoff]]'s roasters in the ''[[Comedy Central Roast#David Hasselhoff|Comedy Central Roast of David Hasselhoff]]''. Starting in the fall of 2011, Hamilton starred as \"Georges\" for the national tour of the [[Tony Award|Tony]]-winning revival of ''[[La Cage aux Folles (musical)|La Cage aux Folles]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://broadwayworld.com/article/George-Hamilton-to-Star-in-National-Tour-of-LA-CAGE-AUX-FOLLES-20110425 |title=George Hamilton to Star in National Tour of LA CAGE AUX FOLLES |publisher=Broadwayworld.com}}</ref> He was still starring in the show {{as of|2012|June|lc=y}}.\n\nIn 2015 George and his ex-wife, Alana Hamilton appeared in Season 4/Episode 10 of Celebrity Wife Swap. Alana swapped with Angela \"Big Ang\" Raiola of Mob Wives fame, and her husband, Neil Murphy. In the summer of 2016, Hamilton appeared in television commercials for [[KFC]] as the \"Extra Crispy Colonel,\" a deeply tanned version of the company's mascot, [[Colonel Sanders]], a role which he returned to in the spring of 2018. In the summer of 2018, Hamilton will portray the Colonel on ''[[General Hospital]]''.<ref name=\"Rice\"/>\n\n==Business endeavors and misc==\nIn the late 1980s Hamilton launched the George Hamilton Skin Care System and the George Hamilton Sun Care System and tanning salons.<ref>{{cite book |title=Marketing Madness: A Survival Guide For A Consumer Society |last=Jacobson |first=Michael |last2=Masur |first2=Laurie |last3=Collins |first3=Ron |year=1995 |publisher=Westview Press |location= |isbn=978-0-8133-1980-3 |page=[https://archive.org/details/marketingmadness00jacorich/page/60 60] |pages= |url=https://archive.org/details/marketingmadness00jacorich |url-access=registration |accessdate= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Where the Sun Shines, There He Is |author=Alexander, Ron |newspaper=The New York Times |date=September 19, 1989 |url= }}</ref> A cigar lounge bearing his name was opened in the late 1990s at the [[New York-New York Hotel and Casino|New York, New York, hotel]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]] and other locations, along with a line of cigars bearing the actor's name. A January 1998 article in ''Cigar Aficionado'' magazine described Hamilton's style as \"[[Cary Grant]] meets [[Pat Riley]]\".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Benes |first1=Alejandro |last2= |first2= |year= |title=Hamiltons Las Vegas |journal=CigarAficionado |publisher=CigarAficionado |volume=Mar-Apr 1998 |issue= |pages= |url= |doi= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Minkoff |first1=Alysse |last2= |first2= |year= |title=Forever Suave|journal=CigarAficionado |publisher=CigarAficionado |volume=Jan-Feb 1998 |issue= |pages= |url= |doi= }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=|first1= |last2= |first2= |year= |title=Smoke a Stogie|journal=Los Angeles Magazine |publisher= |volume=Oct 1999 |issue= |pages= |url= |doi= }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2006 Hamilton served as grand marshal for the 79th Annual [[Shenandoah Apple Blossom Festival]] in [[Winchester, Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebloom.com/celebrities-past.html |title=Past Shenandoah Apple Blossom Festivals |accessdate=July 24, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716223202/http://www.thebloom.com/celebrities-past.html |archivedate=July 16, 2011 }}</ref> In 2016 and 2018, Hamilton appeared as the \"Crispy Colonel\" in commercials for [[KFC]], playing on his \"Tan Man\" image.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/george-hamilton-reprises-his-role-as-colonel-sanders-i-m-guy-who-has-parlayed-a-tan-a-career-1104003|title=George Hamilton Reprises His Role as Colonel Sanders: \"I'm the Only Guy Who Has Parlayed a Tan Into a Career\"|website=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1966 Hamilton had a relationship with [[Lynda Bird Johnson]], the daughter of US President [[Lyndon B. Johnson]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/reliable-source/post/lynda-johnson-robb-and-george-hamilton-when-a-presidents-daughter-dated-a-movie-star/2012/02/10/gIQAuXZO9Q_blog.html |title=Lynda Johnson Robb and George Hamilton: When a president\u2019s daughter dated a movie star |newspaper=Washington Post }}</ref> Hamilton was married to actress [[Alana Stewart]] from 1972 to 1975. Their son, [[Ashley Hamilton]], was born in 1974. George Thomas Hamilton is his younger son (born in December 1999) with his ex-girlfriend Kimberly Blackford.\n\nThe divorced Hamiltons reunited in the mid-1990s to co-host a daytime talk show, ''[[George and Alana]]''. In ''I'm A Celebrity'' he revealed he had dated at least four Miss Worlds. Hamilton has a well-known social relationship with [[Imelda Marcos]], the widow of former [[Philippines]] president [[Ferdinand Marcos]]. It was later revealed that he also had business ties to the Marcoses. In 1990 Hamilton was named as an unindicted co-conspirator in a federal fraud and racketeering case against the Marcoses involving looting Philippine government funds; Imelda was acquitted in the case.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-10-09/news/mn-2056_1_beverly-hills | first1=William C. | last1=Rempel | first2=Henry | last2=Weinstein | work=Los Angeles Times | date=October 9, 1990 | title=COLUMN ONE : An Actor's Close Ties to Marcos : The Philippine government's quest for missing funds leads to George Hamilton's former doorstep in Beverly Hills}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Burt Reynolds]]' autobiography,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Reynolds|first1=Burt |year=1994 |title=My Life |url=https://archive.org/details/mylifereyn00reyn|url-access=registration|publisher=Hyperion Books |ISBN=978-0-7868-6130-9 }}</ref> Hamilton has a healthy sense of humor, even when the humor is directed at him: Reynolds once made up a [[birthday card]] for Hamilton with a composite photograph of [[Tony Curtis]] and [[Anthony Perkins]], titled \"To George, love from Mum and Dad\". Hamilton found the card hilarious and showed it to everybody. ''[[My One and Only (film)|My One and Only]]'', a 2009 comedy film starring Logan Lerman, was loosely based on a story about George Hamilton's early life on the road with his mother and brother, featuring anecdotes that Hamilton had told to [[Merv Griffin]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[Lone Star (1952 film)|Lone Star]]'' (1952) as Noah (uncredited)\n* ''[[Crime and Punishment U.S.A.]]'' (1959) as Robert\n* ''[[Home from the Hill (film)|Home from the Hill]]'' (1960) as Theron Hunnicutt\n* ''[[All the Fine Young Cannibals]]'' (1960) as Tony McDowall\n* ''[[Where the Boys Are]]'' (1960) as Ryder Smith\n* ''[[Angel Baby (1961 film)|Angel Baby]]'' (1961) as Paul Strand\n* ''[[By Love Possessed (film)|By Love Possessed]]'' (1961) as Warren Winner\n* ''[[A Thunder of Drums]]'' (1961) as Lt. Curtis McQuade\n* ''[[Light in the Piazza (film)|The Light in the Piazza]]'' (1962) as Fabrizio Naccarelli\n* ''[[Two Weeks in Another Town]]'' (1962) as Davie Drew\n* ''[[The Victors (film)|The Victors]]'' (1963) as Cpl. Theodore Trower\n* ''[[Act One (film)|Act One]]'' (1963) as Moss Hart\n* ''[[Looking for Love (film)|Looking for Love]]'' (1964) as Himself (Cameo)\n* ''[[Your Cheatin' Heart (film)|Your Cheatin' Heart]]'' (1964) as Hank Williams\n* ''[[Viva Maria!]]'' (1965) as Flores\n* ''[[That Man George]]'' (1966) as George\n* ''[[Doctor, You've Got to Be Kidding!]]'' (1967) as Harlan Wycliff\n* ''[[A Time for Killing]]'' (1967) as Capt. Dorrit Bentley\n* ''[[Jack of Diamonds (1967 film)|Jack of Diamonds]]'' (1967) as Jeff Hill\n* ''[[The Power (1968 film)|The Power]]'' (1968) as Prof. Jim Tanner\n* ''Togetherness'' (1970) as Jack DuPont\n* ''[[Elvis: That's the Way It Is]]'' (1970) (documentary)\n* ''[[Evel Knievel (1971 film)|Evel Knievel]]'' (1971) as Evel Knievel\n* ''[[The Man Who Loved Cat Dancing (film)|The Man Who Loved Cat Dancing]]'' (1973) as Willard Crocker\n* ''[[Medusa (1973 film)|Medusa]]'' (1973) as Jeffrey\n* ''[[Jacqueline Susann's Once Is Not Enough (film)|Once Is Not Enough]]'' (1975) as David Milford\n* ''[[Roots (1977 miniseries)|Roots]]'' (TV series/film) (1977)\n* ''[[The Happy Hooker Goes to Washington]]'' (1977) as Ward Thompson\n* ''The Magnificent Hustle'' (1978) as Donald Hightower\n* ''[[Sextette]]'' (1978) as Vance Norton\n* ''[[The Users (film)|The Users]]'' (1978) as Adam Baker\n* ''[[From Hell to Victory]]'' (1979) as Maurice Bernard\n* ''[[Love at First Bite]]'' (1979) as Count Vladimir Dracula\n* ''[[Death Car on the Freeway]]'' (1979) as Ray Jeffries\n* ''[[Zorro, The Gay Blade]]'' (1981) as Zorro The Gay Blade / Don Diego Vega / Bunny Wigglesworth\n* ''[[Malibu (film)|Malibu]]'' (1983) as Jay Pomerantz\n* ''[[Poker Alice (film)|Poker Alice]]'' (1987) as Cousin John Moffit\n* ''[[The Godfather Part III]]'' (1990) as B. J. Harrison\n* ''[[List of Columbo episodes#Season 10 and specials|Columbo: Caution: Murder can be Hazardous to your Health]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Doc Hollywood]]'' (1991) as Doctor Halberstrom\n* ''[[Once Upon a Crime]]'' (1992) as Alfonso de la Pena\n* ''[[Amore! (1993 film)|Amore!]]'' (1993) as Rudolpho Carbonera\n* ''[[Double Dragon (film)|Double Dragon]]'' (1994) as Channel 102 News Anchor (uncredited)\n* ''[[Vanished (1995 film)|Vanished]]'' (1995 TV movie) as Malcolm Patterson\n* ''Playback'' (1996) as Gil Braman\n* ''[[Meet Wally Sparks]]'' (1997) as Himself\n* ''[[8 Heads in a Duffel Bag]]'' (1997) as Dick Bennett\n* ''[[Bulworth]]'' (1998) as Himself (cameo) (uncredited)\n* ''[[Casper Meets Wendy]]'' (1998) as Desmond Spellman\n* ''She's Too Tall'' (1999) as Alonso Palermo\n* ''[[Off Key]]'' (2001) as Armand\n* ''[[Crocodile Dundee in Los Angeles]]'' (2001) as Himself (cameo)\n* ''Reflections of Evil'' (2002) as Duncan Carlyle\n* ''[[Hollywood Ending]]'' (2002) as Ed\n* ''Pets'' (1999) as Von Steiger ('The Hand')\n* ''The Little Unicorn'' (2002)\n* ''A Very Cool Christmas'' / Too Cool For Christmas'' (2004) as Santa Claus\n* ''[[The L.A. Riot Spectacular]]'' (2005) as The King of Beverly Hills\n* ''[[Rumor Has It (film)|Rumor Has It...]]'' (2005) as Himself (cameo) (uncredited)\n* ''Melvin Smarty'' (2012) as Hitman / Mexican Colonel\n* ''[[Rosemary Rodriguez|Silver Skies]]'' (2016) as Phil\n* ''[[The Congressman]]'' (2016) as Laird Devereaux\n* ''[[Swiped]]'' (2018) as Phil Singer\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Television work==\n{{Div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* ''[[The Donna Reed Show]]'' (as Herbie Shields in \"Have Fun\", 1959) as Herbie Shields\n* ''The Rogues'' (one episode  as Jamie, 1964) as Jamie\n* ''A Farewell to Arms'' (1966) (miniseries) as Lt. Frederick Henry\n* ''[[Harold Robbins' The Survivors]]'' (1969) as Duncan Carlyle\n* ''Paris 7000'' (1970) (canceled after 10 episodes) as Jack Brennan\n* ''The Last of the Powerseekers'' (1971) as Duncan Carlyle\n* ''[[The Dead Don't Die (1975 film)|The Dead Don't Die]]'' (1975) as Don Drake\n* ''[[List of Columbo episodes#Season 4|Columbo: A Deadly State of Mind]]'' (1975) as Dr Marcus Collier\n* ''Roots'' (1977) (miniseries) as Stephen Bennett\n* ''McCloud: The Great Taxicab Stampede'' (1977) as Keith Hampton\n* ''The Strange Possession of Mrs. Oliver'' (1977) as Greg Oliver\n* ''Killer on Board'' (1977) as Glenn Lyle\n* ''The Users'' (1978) as Adam Baker\n* ''[[The Eddie Capra Mysteries]]'' (1978&nbsp;\u2013 Episode: \"Nightmare at Pendragon Castle\")\n* ''[[The Seekers (1979 film)|The Seekers]]'' (1979) as Lt. Hamilton Stovall\n* ''Institute for Revenge'' (1979) as Alan Roberto\n* ''Express to Terror'' (1979) (pilot for Supertrain) as David Belnik\n* ''[[Death Car on the Freeway]]'' (1979) as Ray Jeffries\n* ''The Great Cash Giveaway Getaway'' (1980) as Hightower\n* ''[[The Fantastic Miss Piggy Show]]'' (1982, TV Special) as himself\n* ''[[Malibu (film)|Malibu]]'' (1983) (miniseries) as Jay Pomerantz\n* ''[[Two Fathers' Justice]]'' (1985) as Trent Bradley\n* ''[[Dynasty (1981 TV series)|Dynasty]]'' (cast member from 1985\u20131986) as [[Joel Abrigore]]\n* ''[[Monte Carlo (miniseries)|Monte Carlo]]'' (1986) (miniseries) as Harry Price\n* ''[[Spies (TV series)|Spies]]'' (1987) as Ian Stone\n* ''Poker Alice'' (1987, based on the frontier gambler [[Poker Alice]]) as Cousin John Moffit\n* ''[[List of Columbo episodes#Season 10 and specials|Columbo: Caution: Murder Can Be Hazardous to Your Health]]'' (1991) as Wade Anders\n* ''The House on Sycamore Street'' (1992) as J.D. Gantry / Harry Lennox\n* ''[[List of Birds of a Feather episodes#Series 5|Birds of a Feather: It Happened in Hollywood]]'' (1993) as Himself\n* ''Das Paradies am Ende der Berge'' (1993) as Earl Henry von Hohenlodern\n* ''[[Two Fathers: Justice for the Innocent]]'' (1994) as Bradley\n* ''[[The Bold and the Beautiful]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[George & Alana]]'' (1995\u20131996)\n* ''Vanished'' (1995) as Malcolm Patterson\n* ''The Guilt'' (1996) as Alan Van Buren\n* ''[[Hart to Hart]]'': Till Death Do Us Hart (1996) as Karl Von Ostenberg\n* ''[[Rough Riders (miniseries)|Rough Riders]]'' (1997) as [[William Randolph Hearst]]\n* ''[[Miss USA]]'' & ''[[Miss Universe]]'' (1997) as Host\n* ''[[Jenny (TV series)|Jenny]]'' (1997\u20131998) as Guy Hathaway\n* ''[[Casper Meets Wendy]]'' (1998) as Desmond Spellman\n* ''[[Baywatch]]'' (1 episode: season 9, episode 21) (1999) as Earl / Himself\n* ''P.T. Barnum'' (1999) as Francis Olmsted\n* ''The Family'' (2003) as Host\n* ''[[Las Vegas (TV series)|Las Vegas]]'' (guest appearance 2004) as Bernard Taylor\n* ''Too Cool for Christmas'' (2004) as Santa Claus\n* ''[[Joey (TV series)|Joey]]'' (guest appearance 2005)\n* ''[[Dancing with the Stars]]'' (cast member in 2006)\n* ''[[I'm a Celebrity...Get Me Out of Here! (UK series 9)|I'm A Celebrity Get Me Out Of Here!]]'' (2009) as Himself\n* ''The Comedy Central Roast Of David Hasselhoff'' (2010) as Himself&nbsp;\u2013 Roaster\n* ''[[Hot in Cleveland]]'' (2013) as Robin\n* ''[[Stewarts & Hamiltons]]'' (8 episodes, 2015) as Himself\n* ''[[Wife Swap (U.S. TV series)|Celebrity Wife Swap]]'' (1 episode, 2015) as Himself\n* ''[[2 Broke Girls]]'' (1 episode as Bob, 2016) as Bob\n* ''[[American Housewife]]'' (recurring, 2017\u20132019) as Spencer Blitz<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/tv/2017/09/07/george-hamilton-american-housewife-season-2/ |title=George Hamilton joins season 2 of American Housewife |last=Holub |first=Christian |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=September 7, 2017 |accessdate=September 9, 2017}}</ref>\n* ''[[General Hospital]]'' (July 6, 2018) as [[Colonel Sanders]]<ref name=\"Rice\">{{cite magazine|url=http://ew.com/tv/2018/07/04/general-hospital-george-hamilton-colonel-sanders/|title=General Hospital: See how George Hamilton will show up as Colonel Sanders|first=Lynette|last=Rice|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=[[New York City]]|date=July 4, 2018|accessdate=June 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* ''[[Grace and Frankie]]'' (1 episode, 2019) as Jack Patterson\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Books==\n* ''Life's Little Pleasures'' (co-authored with [[Alysse Minkoff]]) (1998)  {{ISBN|978-1575440866}}\n* ''Don't Mind If I Do or do I'' (co-authored with William Stadiem) (2009) {{ISBN|978-1416545071}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|1313|George Hamilton}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* [http://encyclopediaofarkansas.net/encyclopedia/entry-detail.aspx?entryID=6441 Encyclopedia of Arkansas History & Culture]\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for George Hamilton\n| list =\n{{Golden Globe Award for New Star of the Year Actor}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Actor}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamilton, George}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:New Star of the Year (Actor) Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Participants in American reality television series]]\n[[Category:MGM Records artists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer contract players]]\n[[Category:Hackley School alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision work", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Hamilton_(actor)"}
{"title_page": "Loop Service", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Loop Trolley]] in St. Louis}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name             = Loop Service\n| other_name       = {{plainlist}}\n* A Loop/B Loop\n* Central Loop Line (2012\u20132015)\n{{endplainlist}}\n| color            = {{TMTC color|B}}\n| color2           = {{TMTC color|A}}\n| logo             = Portland Streetcar symbol.svg\n| logo_width      = 30px\n| image            = Streetcar on Tilikum Crossing with fog-shrouded hills in background, 11-2015.jpg\n| image_width      = 250px\n| image_alt        = \n| caption          = A B Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015\n| type             = [[Streetcar]]\n| system           = [[Portland Streetcar]]\n| status           = Operational\n| locale           = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S.\n| start            = \n| end              = \n| stations         = 52\n| routes           = 2\n| daily_ridership  = {{plainlist}}\n* '''A Loop:''' 3,612\n* '''B Loop:''' 3,064\n{{endplainlist}}{{br}}({{as of|2018|September|lc=yes}})<ref name=\"portland-streetcar-ridership-counts-2018-09\">{{cite news |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Ridership-Counts-2018-09.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Ridership Counts, July 2015 - Present (By Fiscal Year) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=September 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n{{endplainlist}}\n| ridership2       =\n| open             = {{start date|2012|09|22}}\n| event1label      = \n| event1           = \n| event2label      = \n| event2           = \n| event3label      = \n| event3           = \n| owner            = [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]]\n| operator         = Portland Streetcar, Inc.{{br}}[[TriMet]]\n| character        = [[At-grade]], mixed between [[street running]] and exclusive lane\n| depot            = \n| stock            = \n| linelength       = {{convert|5.6|mi|km|abbr=on}} (per direction)\n| tracklength_mi   = \n| tracks           = \n| gauge            = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge        = \n| load_gauge       = \n| minradius        = \n| racksystem       = \n| routenumber      = \n| linenumber       = \n| electrification  = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct Current|DC]], [[overhead line|overhead catenary]]\n| speed_mph        = \n| elevation_ft     = \n| website          = \n| map              = {{Portland Streetcar CL Line}}\n| map_name         = Route diagram\n| map_state        = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''Loop Service''' is a [[streetcar]] [[circle route|circle line]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, that is part of the [[Portland Streetcar]] system. Operated by Portland Streetcar, Inc. and [[TriMet]], it consists of two distinct services: the '''A Loop''', which runs [[clockwise]], and the '''B Loop''', which runs counterclockwise. Each service travels a {{convert|5.6|mi|km|1|adj=on}} loop between [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|downtown Portland]] and the [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]], crossing the [[Willamette River]] on the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in the north and [[Tilikum Crossing]] in the south. The line connects Portland's downtown, [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]], and [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]. It serves the city's various landmarks and institutions, including the [[Rose Quarter, Portland, Oregon|Rose Quarter]], the [[Oregon Convention Center]], the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI), [[Oregon Health and Science University]] (OHSU), and [[Portland State University]] (PSU).\n\nPortland city officials first proposed building an eastside streetcar line in 1997, at the same time the city council authorized the construction of the [[NS Line|first streetcar line]] in downtown. After several years of planning, the city council adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in 2003. Upon its inaugural service in 2012, the Loop Service was known as the '''Central Loop Line''' ('''CL Line'''). It initially ran from Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to OMSI via the Pearl District. It was re-branded to its current name upon the opening of Tilikum Crossing bridge in 2015.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\">{{cite web|title=Portland Streetcar Loop Service |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |archivedate=August 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Broadway Bridge west end.jpg|thumb|left|The Broadway Bridge in 2009, prior to the installation of streetcar tracks]]\n\nPlans to expand the Portland Streetcar east of the [[Willamette River]] emerged in July 1997, at the same time the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] authorized the construction of the system's [[NS Line|first line]] on the west side between [[Northwest District, Portland, Oregon|Northwest Portland]] and [[Portland State University|PSU]]. During this time, the council also voted to fund a $16.7&nbsp;million retrofitting of the [[Hawthorne Bridge]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Closure launches bridge make over |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 22, 1998 |page=D2}}</ref> which they had anticipated would carry a future streetcar line between [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry|OMSI]] and the [[Oregon Convention Center]]. This line was one of many proposed by the Buckman Neighborhood Association for the east side.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Streetcars will return to Portland; the city council votes to pay for a westside loop of streetcars described as cheaper than light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 31, 1997 |page=D1}}</ref> The Hawthorne Bridge reopened in April 1999, with the outer-lane decks rebuilt to accommodate notches for rails.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Wait no more: Sunday makrs Hawthorne Bridge reopening |date=April 24, 1999 |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=C1}}</ref> In July 2001, another streetcar plan was proposed as part of the Lloyd District Development Strategy.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\">{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Lloyd-District-Development-Strategy-Full-2001-07-27.pdf |title=Lloyd District Development Strategy |publisher=[[Prosper Portland|Portland Development Commission]] |date=July 27, 2001 |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Portland grand plans works in works in Lloyd District |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 17, 2001 |page=B3}}</ref> This strategy sought the addition of streetcars to the [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]], which was already being served by buses and [[MAX Light Rail]],<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|20}} to create a [[transit hub]] by adding lines on Broadway and Weidler avenues.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|26}} The extension would connect with the west side via the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=New streetcar route follows different mission |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 20, 2001 |page=24}}</ref> This plan was supported by concurrent efforts to revitalize nearby [[Rose Quarter]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Vision for Rose Quarter outlined |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 13, 2001 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn a series of meetings that began in February 2003, an advisory committee composed of eastside residents urged extending this proposed Broadway\u2013Weidler alignment up to 21st Avenue. Meanwhile, Portland Streetcar officials, amid [[TriMet]] plans to construct a new Willamette River crossing as part of a [[MAX Orange Line|MAX extension to Milwaukie]], suggested routing the streetcar along this new bridge proposal instead of the Hawthorne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar officials seek Eastside desire |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 17, 2003 |page=E2}}</ref> The city council, with backing from [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] commissioners, adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in June 2003.<ref name=\"eastside-study\">{{cite web |title=Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study |date=June 25, 2003 |publisher=City of Portland Office of Transportation |url=https://scholarsbank.uoregon.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1794/5259/Portland_Eastside_Streetcar_Study.pdf |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The study outlined a three-phased eastside loop project that ran from the Broadway Bridge to the Lloyd District, then south through Grand Avenue and [[Oregon Route 99E|Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard]] to Hawthorne Boulevard. A southern crossing back to the west side depended upon whether the new bridge would be constructed, leaving that section undetermined at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar backers propose loop through Inner Eastside |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 6, 2003 |page=D2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stern |first1=Henry |last2=Nkrumah |first2=Wade |title=City Council watch |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 26, 2003 |page=C2}}</ref>\n\n===Funding and construction===\n\n[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] regional government approved the streetcar extension in July 2006 followed by the city council in September 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGrain |first=Maureen |title=Metro says yes to expansion for streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=July 28, 2006 |url=http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/07/31/story11.html |accessdate=May 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"extension-green-light\">{{cite news |last=Mayer |first=James |date=September 7, 2007 |title=Streetcar extension gets green light |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> The total cost of the project was $148.8{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|148800000|2012}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), including the cost to purchase additional vehicles.<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\">{{cite report |url=https://www.transit.dot.gov/sites/fta.dot.gov/files/docs/funding/grant-programs/capital-investments/115401/2016-oregon-portland-streetcar-loop-project.pdf |title=Streetcar Loop Project Before-and-After Study (2016) |publisher=[[Federal Transit Administration]] |date=2016 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|19}} Just over half would be paid for with federal funds.<ref name=\"wweek20120822\">{{cite web |title=Slow Ride |url=https://www.wweek.com/portland/article-19584-slow_ride.html |first=Aaron |last=Mesh |date=August 22, 2012 |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref> The city council committed to allocating $27{{nbsp}}million of city funds.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\"/> $20{{nbsp}}million from the state, $15.5{{nbsp}}million from a Local Improvement District, and a combination of various other local or regional sources completed the locally matched financing.<ref name=\"factsheetMay2010\">{{cite web |title=Portland Streetcar Loop fact sheet (May 2010) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |accessdate=August 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821075510/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |archive-date=August 21, 2010 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> On April 30, 2009, U.S. [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Transportation Secretary]] [[Ray LaHood]] announced $75{{nbsp}}million in federal funding for the project, the full amount that had been requested by Portland. This allocation, secured in large part through the efforts of Oregon [[United States House of Representatives|Representatives]] [[Earl Blumenauer]] and [[Peter DeFazio]], was the largest and final component of the financing plan and meant the project could proceed with construction.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pope |first1=Charles |last2=Rivera |first2=Dylan |title=Feds approve $75 million for streetcar expansion |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005165644/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |archive-date=October 5, 2012 |url-status=unfit}}</ref><ref name=\"Fedsgive\">{{cite news |title=Feds give $75 million for Oregon streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily46.html?surround=lfn |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United Streetcar 10T3 prototype for Portland.jpg|thumb|left|Unveiling of the United Streetcar 10T3 prototype in July 2009]]\n\nIn 2005, the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] approved a spending bill that included $4{{nbsp}}million for a locally produced streetcar vehicle.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |last=Hamilton |first=Don |title=Iron firm forges streetcar desire |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 5, 2005 |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331125621/https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |archive-date=March 31, 2012}}</ref> That money went to [[Oregon Iron Works]], which created the subsidiary [[United Streetcar]] upon receiving the contract to build new streetcars for the Portland Streetcar.<ref name=\"streetcarcontract\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Oregon Iron Works gets contract for streetcar |date=January 26, 2007 |newspaper=[[Portland Business Journal]] |url=https://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2007/01/22/daily45.html |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> In May 2009, United Streetcar delivered its first prototype to Portland for testing on existing tracks; it was the first U.S.-built streetcar in nearly 60 years.<ref name=\"trib-2009may14\">{{cite news |last=MacKinnon |first=Mary |title=Streetcars soon to be made in Oregon |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=May 14, 2009<!--(later re-dated May 13)--> |url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=49492 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> That August, the city signed a $20{{nbsp}}million contract to purchase six new streetcars from the manufacturer for the eastside extension.<ref name=\"Oreg14Aug09\">{{cite news |last=Rivera |first=Dylan |title=Portland inks $20 million deal for locally made streetcars |date=August 14, 2009 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817123910/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archivedate=17 August 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGroundbreaking for the Eastside Streetcar Loop project took place on June 25, 2009. The city selected [[Stacy and Witbeck]] to be the project's general contractor and actual construction began the following year.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/construction-begins-eastside-streetcar-loop/ |last=Baer |first=April |title=Construction Begins On Eastside Streetcar Loop |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=June 25, 2009 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Across the alignment, crews laid tracks in three- to four-block increments; by February 2010, they were laying tracks on Northeast Grand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/02/09/streetcar-loop-project/ |title=Streetcar Loop Project |last=Carter |first=Dan |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=February 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The Broadway Bridge was closed to all traffic to be renovated from July 19 to September 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |title=Portland \u2013 Broadway Bridge will close |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> To maintain the existing weight of the bridge (this was necessary to allow the bridge to continue lifting its spans) and simultaneously add tracks, lighter fiber-reinforced concrete replaced the deck.<ref name=\"streetcar work\">{{cite news|last=Rose|first=Joseph |title=Streetcar work shutting down Broadway Bridge |date=July 5, 2010 <!--(July 4 online edition)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=A10 |url=https://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2010/07/streetcar_work_shuts_broadway.html |accessdate=November 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wrap-up-broadway\">{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/02/18/streetcar-work-almost-finished-on-broadway-bridge/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Streetcar work wraps up on Broadway Bridge |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=February 18, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], sections of two former two-way streets\u2014Northwest Lovejoy and Northwest Northrup\u2014were converted into one-way streets following the addition of streetcar tracks. Work completed in this section upon the reopening of the Lovejoy ramp on the west end of the Broadway Bridge in November 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/11/05/pearl-streets-reopen-with-changed-traffic-patterns/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Pearl streets reopen with changed traffic patterns |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=November 5, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In Southeast Portland, crews built a {{convert|425|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} bridge that led the streetcar to OMSI, the project's eastern terminus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/12/22/portland-streetcar-flyover-bridge-near-omsi/ |last=Carter |first=Dan |title=Portland Streetcar flyover bridge near OMSI |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=December 22, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Barber Block sunlit with streetcar, 2012.jpg|thumb|right|Car 015 in front of the [[Barber Block]] on Southeast Grand Avenue in 2012]] \n\nIn July 2011, the city council agreed to contractual changes that reduced the number of streetcars on order from six to five.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/07/20/eastside-streetcar-loop-will-be-delayed-number-of-cars-reduced/ |last=Webber |first=Angela |title=Eastside streetcar loop will be delayed, number of cars reduced |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=July 20, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> United Streetcar had depended on [[Czech Republic|Czech]] firm [[\u0160koda Transportation|\u0160koda]], which built the system's first streetcars, to build the new streetcars' propulsion system but these failed acceptance testing. Portland officials opted instead to source the propulsion system from [[Wisconsin]]-based [[Rockwell Automation]], but the design was still being developed at the time. They then pursued [[Austria]]n manufacturer Elin to produce a propulsion system for the prototype while they awaited Rockwell. Changes to the propulsion system necessitated changes to the streetcar design in order for the streetcar to accommodate a different form factor; this ultimately delayed the project and raised the cost of manufacturing.<ref name=\"oreg-2011jul19\">{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 19, 2011 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Opening and extension===\n\nThe {{convert|3.3|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} streetcar extension opened on September 22, 2012, after a five-month-long delay.<ref name=\"PS-History\">{{cite web|title=Streetcar History |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013400/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |date=July 19, 2011 |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> Its inaugural service, branded the Central Loop Line (abbreviated as CL Line), ran from Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to OMSI via the Lloyd District.<ref name=\"PS-History\"/> Service along the eastside segment operated with frequencies of 18 minutes instead of the planned 15 minutes due to funding cuts by TriMet and the City of Portland, as well as delays in streetcar delivery from United Streetcar. At the time of opening, fares were $1 following the elimination of the city's [[Fareless Square|Free Rail Zone]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rose (journalist) |date=September 21, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar's eastside loop gets off to hobbled start Saturday |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2012/09/portland_streetcars_eastside_l.html |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar Introduces \u2018Central Loop\u2019 Service |url=http://newsmanager.commpartners.com/aptapt/issues/2012-10-05/3.html |work=Passenger Transport |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> Approximately 3,200 riders per weekday used the line during the first two weeks of service.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2012/10/31/eastside-streetcar-carrying-the-wait.html |last=Giegerich |first=Andy |title=Eastside streetcar: Carrying the wait |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=October 31, 2012 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2015, service was extended {{convert|0.9|mi|km}} on the west side from Southwest 10th and Market streets along existing NS Line tracks south to Southwest Moody and Meade streets in the [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]].<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\"/>{{rp|19}} A new temporary schedule eliminated the name CL Line in favor of two separate routes\u2014A Loop and B Loop. Streetcars began operating across the newly built [[Tilikum Crossing]], but without carrying passengers across the bridge during a two-week transitional \"pre-revenue service\" phase.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/> The line was formally re-branded as the Loop Service on September 12, 2015,<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.oregonmetro.gov/sites/default/files/2018/12/07/RTP-Appendix_G_CTP_20160614.pdf |title=2018 Regional Transportation Plan: Coordinated transportation plan for seniors and people with disabilities |publisher=[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] |date=December 6, 2018 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2\u201313}} when the {{convert|1720|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} Tilikum Crossing opened to the public and began permitting streetcars to carry passengers on the route section across the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/pm/Fact-sheets-timelines/TC_2Page_June2014.pdf |title=Tilikum Crossing, Bridge of the People, brings new connections and new options in 2015 |publisher=TriMet |date=June 2014 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/><ref name=\"PS-History\"/><ref name=\"tilikum-factsheet-2014\">{{cite news |last=Vincent |first=John M. |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Routes, fares change with expanded streetcar service |url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |newspaper=[[The Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |page=A3 |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128143529/http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |archivedate=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Route==\n[[File:A Lloyd via Peral (21612375879).jpg|thumb|right|An A Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015]]\n[[File:Portland Streetcar car 023 at west end of Broadway Bridge in 2016.jpg|thumb|right|A B Loop streetcar crossing the Broadway Bridge in 2016]]\n\nThe Loop Service forms a {{convert|5.6|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[circle route]] between downtown Portland and the Central Eastside.<ref>{{cite map |url=https://www.transitmap.net/portland-streetcar-2015/ |title=Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=2015 |via=transitmap.net}}</ref> A majority of each route runs on one-way single-track. From their original endpoint on Southwest Market Street, the A and B Loops travel northbound through downtown Portland to the Pearl District along NS Line tracks on 10th and 11th avenues.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+10th+%26+Clay/@45.5150904,-122.6838684,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a07f9361b:0x48d11b9676b62d09!8m2!3d45.5144961!4d-122.6849739 |title=SW 10th & Clay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+11th+%26+Clay/@45.5152692,-122.6853204,18z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a1bc20dab:0x5353b61f171ae97b!8m2!3d45.5151856!4d-122.6860428 |title=SW 11th & Clay |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The services meet at the intersection of Northwest 10th and Lovejoy where they proceed east towards the Broadway Bridge using the Eastside Loop extension tracks.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NW+9th+%26+Lovejoy/@45.5300511,-122.6789145,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x549509fe395af473:0x1f39de6a4894f631!8m2!3d45.5300534!4d-122.6806308 |title=NW 9th & Lovejoy |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> After crossing the Willamette River on this bridge, the tracks again split, with the A Loop tracks continuing east on Weidler Street and the B Loop tracks on Broadway Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/N+Weidler+%26+Ross/@45.5339555,-122.6694082,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523bc453bf:0xdf7d65ef2959f0dc!8m2!3d45.5344683!4d-122.6694356 |title=N Weidler & Ross |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Broadway+%26+Ross+(Streetcar)/@45.5337533,-122.6705135,17.04z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523a89db6d:0x734a73024c507be4!8m2!3d45.53445!4d-122.6695217 |title=NE Broadway & Ross (Streetcar) |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The B Loop turns right on Northeast Grand Avenue and proceeds south through to OMSI.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Grand+%26+Broadway/@45.533741,-122.6611424,17.83z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a74cee1672d9:0x4eb3a0bcd277cf43!8m2!3d45.5347981!4d-122.6605477 |title=NE Grand & Broadway |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right on Northeast 7th Avenue.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Halsey+Southbound/@45.5318626,-122.6610966,17.29z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b333c19a1d:0x22d53ea9dc86a0cb!8m2!3d45.5334298!4d-122.6585944 |title=NE 7th & Halsey Southbound |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Both tracks intersect MAX Light Rail tracks on Holladay Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Holladay/@45.5299588,-122.6609103,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b25eeab5ef:0xa0465a316dd28817!8m2!3d45.5308073!4d-122.6586092 |title=NE 7th & Holladay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns left on Northeast Oregon street, turns left again in front of the Oregon Convention Center, and heads south on Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Oregon+%26+Grand/@45.5286027,-122.6627257,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0adec0981b1:0xa2326856bed21290!8m2!3d45.5286869!4d-122.6604364 |title=NE Oregon & Grand |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The lines rejoin and enter an overpass at Southeast Harrison Street, which carries them to OMSI and Tilikum Crossing.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SE+Water%2FOMSI+(Streetcar)/@45.5079612,-122.6631697,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a7236697d75:0x40bba82a7a827677!8m2!3d45.5069508!4d-122.663364 |title=SE Water/OMSI (Streetcar) |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the A and B Loop routes cross the river back to the west side, they re-merge with the NS Line alignment on Southwest Moody Avenue. The tracks turn left onto Southwest River Parkway, which turns into Southwest Harrison Street. They turn right on Southwest 4th Street, then left on Southwest Montgomery Street, and split again at Southwest 5th Avenue. The A Loop crosses PSU's [[Urban Plaza]] diagonally for Southwest Mill Street and the B Loop turns right on Southwest 5th Avenue.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/PSU+Urban+Center/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a112fe8f51f:0xb93dc6c9ec4eada!8m2!3d45.5122199!4d-122.6820778 |title=PSU Urban Center |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+5th+%26+Montgomery/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a11485235eb:0x54962f4617846156!8m2!3d45.5117905!4d-122.6812866 |title=SW 5th & Montgomery |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right at Southwest 10th Avenue and returns to the intersection of Southwest 10th and Market. The B Loop turns left onto Southwest Market Street and proceeds left until it returns to Southwest 11th and Market. \n\n===Stations===\n\nThe Loop Service serves 52 stations, of which 24 are shared with the NS Line.<ref name=\"maps-schedules\">{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/schedules |title=Maps + Schedules \u2013 Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Each platform is equipped with a [[ticket vending machine]], [[passenger information system|real-time display]] system, and line information signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/ride-guide/how-to-ride |title=Ride Guide |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref> All stations are [[Accessibility|accessible]] to users with [[Physical disability|limited mobility]].<ref name=\"accessibility-info\">{{cite web |url=http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |title=Accessibility Info |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=June 6, 2019 |archive-date=February 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201000132/http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> Connections to MAX Light Rail are available at 10 stops across the line.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Station\n! rowspan=2 | Neighborhood\n! rowspan=2 |Connections and notes<ref name=\"maps-schedules\"/>\n|-\n! A Loop{{br}}(clockwise)\n! B Loop{{br}}(counterclockwise)\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 10th & Northrup\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 11th & Marshall\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 9th & Lovejoy\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Johnson\n| Northwest 11th & Johnson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Glisan\n| Northwest 11th & Glisan\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Couch\n| Northwest 11th & Couch\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[First Regiment Armory Annex|The Armory]], [[Powell's Books|Powell's City of Books]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Alder\n| Southwest 11th & Alder\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\" | [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Central Library\n| Southwest 11th & Taylor\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Library and Galleria stations]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Central Library (Portland, Oregon)|Central Library]]\n|-\n| Art Museum\n| Southwest 11th & Jefferson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland Art Museum]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Clay\n| Southwest 11th & Clay\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Southwest Park & Mill\n| Southwest Park & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[South Park Blocks]]\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Southwest 5th & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| PSU Urban Center\n| Southwest 5th & Montgomery\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[PSU Urban Center stations]]: [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest 3rd & Harrison\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Harrison Street\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest River Parkway & Moody\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Moody & Meade\n| align=\"center\" | [[South Waterfront]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[South Waterfront/Southwest Moody station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Health and Sciences University|OHSU]] Robertson Life Sciences Building, [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | OMSI\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[OMSI/Southeast Water station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]], [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Mill\n| Southeast Grand & Mill\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Hawthorne\n| Southeast Grand & Hawthorne\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Taylor\n| Southeast Grand & Taylor\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Morrison\n| Southeast Grand & Morrison\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Stark\n| Southeast Grand & Stark\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast MLK & East Burnside\n| Southeast Grand & East Burnside\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Oregon Convention Center\n| Northeast Grand & Hoyt\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Convention Center station (TriMet)|Convention Center station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Convention Center]]\n|-\n| Northeast Oregon & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Holladay\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Holladay\n| Northeast Grand & Multnomah\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Northeast 7th Avenue station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Halsey\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Broadway\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & 2nd\n| Northeast Broadway & 2nd\n| \u2014\n|-\n| North Weidler & Ross\n| North Broadway & Ross\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Service==\n\nThe Loop Service operates from 5:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on weekdays, from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on Saturdays, and from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 10:30&nbsp;p.m. on Sundays. Frequencies in each direction range from 15 minutes between 10:00&nbsp;a.m. and 7:00&nbsp;pm on weekdays and Saturdays to 20 minutes on Sundays.<ref name=\"Schedule\">{{cite web |date=August 30, 2015 |title=Streetcar Schedule |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 Portland Streetcar Loop Service]\n*[http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 Portland Streetcar schedule]\n\n{{Portland Transit}}\n{{Streetcars Portland Oregon}}\n{{Portal bar|Oregon|Trains|Transport}}\n\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2012]]\n[[Category:Streetcars in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:TriMet]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|text=the [[Loop Trolley]] in St. Louis}}\n{{Infobox rail line\n| name             = Loop Service\n| other_name       = {{plainlist}}\n* A Loop/B Loop\n* Central Loop Line (2012\u20132015)\n{{endplainlist}}\n| color            = {{TMTC color|B}}\n| color2           = {{TMTC color|A}}\n| logo             = Portland Streetcar symbol.svg\n| logo_width      = 30px\n| image            = Streetcar on Tilikum Crossing with fog-shrouded hills in background, 11-2015.jpg\n| image_width      = 250px\n| image_alt        = \n| caption          = A B Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015\n| type             = [[Streetcar]]\n| system           = [[Portland Streetcar]]\n| status           = Operational\n| locale           = [[Portland, Oregon]], U.S.\n| start            = \n| end              = \n| stations         = 52\n| routes           = 2\n| daily_ridership  = {{plainlist}}\n* '''A Loop:''' 3,612\n* '''B Loop:''' 3,064\n{{endplainlist}}{{br}}({{as of|2018|September|lc=yes}})<ref name=\"portland-streetcar-ridership-counts-2018-09\">{{cite news |url=https://storage.googleapis.com/streetcar/files/Ridership-Counts-2018-09.pdf |title=Portland Streetcar Ridership Counts, July 2015 - Present (By Fiscal Year) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=September 2018 |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n{{endplainlist}}\n| ridership2       =\n| open             = {{start date|2012|09|22}}\n| event1label      = \n| event1           = \n| event2label      = \n| event2           = \n| event3label      = \n| event3           = \n| owner            = [[Government of Portland, Oregon|City of Portland]]\n| operator         = Portland Streetcar, Inc.{{br}}[[TriMet]]\n| character        = [[At-grade]], mixed between [[street running]] and exclusive lane\n| depot            = \n| stock            = \n| linelength       = {{convert|5.6|mi|km|abbr=on}} (per direction)\n| tracklength_mi   = \n| tracks           = \n| gauge            = {{Track gauge|ussg|allk=on}}\n| old_gauge        = \n| load_gauge       = \n| minradius        = \n| racksystem       = \n| routenumber      = \n| linenumber       = \n| electrification  = 750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct Current|DC]], [[overhead line|overhead catenary]]\n| speed_mph        = \n| elevation_ft     = \n| website          = \n| map              = {{Portland Streetcar CL Line}}\n| map_name         = Route diagram\n| map_state        = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''Loop Service''' is a [[streetcar]] [[circle route|circle line]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States, that is part of the [[Portland Streetcar]] system. Operated by Portland Streetcar, Inc. and [[TriMet]], it consists of two distinct services: the '''A Loop''', which runs [[clockwise]], and the '''B Loop''', which runs counterclockwise. Each service travels a {{convert|5.6|mi|km|1|adj=on}} loop between [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|downtown Portland]] and the [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]], crossing the [[Willamette River]] on the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland)|Broadway Bridge]] in the north and [[Tilikum Crossing]] in the south. The line connects Portland's downtown, [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]], and [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]. It serves the city's various landmarks and institutions, including the [[Rose Quarter, Portland, Oregon|Rose Quarter]], the [[Oregon Convention Center]], the [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]] (OMSI), [[Oregon Health and Science University]] (OHSU), and [[Portland State University]] (PSU).\n\nPortland city officials first proposed building an eastside streetcar line in 1997, at the same time the city council authorized the construction of the [[NS Line|first streetcar line]] in downtown. After several years of planning, the city council adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in 2003. Upon its inaugural service in 2012, the Loop Service was known as the '''Central Loop Line''' ('''CL Line'''). It initially ran from Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to OMSI via the Pearl District. It was re-branded to its current name upon the opening of Tilikum Crossing bridge in 2015.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\">{{cite web|title=Portland Streetcar Loop Service |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |publisher=[[Portland Streetcar]] |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 |archivedate=August 6, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Planning===\n[[File:Broadway Bridge west end.jpg|thumb|left|The Broadway Bridge in 2009, prior to the installation of streetcar tracks]]\n\nPlans to expand the Portland Streetcar east of the [[Willamette River]] emerged in July 1997, at the same time the [[Government of Portland, Oregon|Portland City Council]] authorized the construction of the system's [[NS Line|first line]] on the west side between [[Northwest District, Portland, Oregon|Northwest Portland]] and [[Portland State University|PSU]]. During this time, the council also voted to fund a $16.7&nbsp;million retrofitting of the [[Hawthorne Bridge]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Closure launches bridge make over |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=January 22, 1998 |page=D2}}</ref> which they had anticipated would carry a future streetcar line between [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry|OMSI]] and the [[Oregon Convention Center]]. This line was one of many proposed by the Buckman Neighborhood Association for the east side.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Streetcars will return to Portland; the city council votes to pay for a westside loop of streetcars described as cheaper than light rail |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 31, 1997 |page=D1}}</ref> The Hawthorne Bridge reopened in April 1999, with the outer-lane decks rebuilt to accommodate notches for rails.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stewart |first=Bill |title=Wait no more: Sunday makrs Hawthorne Bridge reopening |date=April 24, 1999 |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=C1}}</ref> In July 2001, another streetcar plan was proposed as part of the Lloyd District Development Strategy.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\">{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Lloyd-District-Development-Strategy-Full-2001-07-27.pdf |title=Lloyd District Development Strategy |publisher=[[Prosper Portland|Portland Development Commission]] |date=July 27, 2001 |access-date=August 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Portland grand plans works in works in Lloyd District |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 17, 2001 |page=B3}}</ref> This strategy sought the addition of streetcars to the [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]], which was already being served by buses and [[MAX Light Rail]],<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|20}} to create a [[transit hub]] by adding lines on Broadway and Weidler avenues.<ref name=\"development-strategy-2001\"/>{{rp|26}} The extension would connect with the west side via the [[Broadway Bridge (Portland, Oregon)|Broadway Bridge]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=New streetcar route follows different mission |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 20, 2001 |page=24}}</ref> This plan was supported by concurrent efforts to revitalize nearby [[Rose Quarter]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Vision for Rose Quarter outlined |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 13, 2001 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nIn a series of meetings that began in February 2003, an advisory committee composed of eastside residents urged extending this proposed Broadway\u2013Weidler alignment up to 21st Avenue. Meanwhile, Portland Streetcar officials, amid [[TriMet]] plans to construct a new Willamette River crossing as part of a [[MAX Orange Line|MAX extension to Milwaukie]], suggested routing the streetcar along this new bridge proposal instead of the Hawthorne Bridge.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar officials seek Eastside desire |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=February 17, 2003 |page=E2}}</ref> The city council, with backing from [[Multnomah County, Oregon|Multnomah County]] commissioners, adopted the Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study in June 2003.<ref name=\"eastside-study\">{{cite web |title=Eastside Streetcar Alignment Study |date=June 25, 2003 |publisher=City of Portland Office of Transportation |url=https://scholarsbank.uoregon.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1794/5259/Portland_Eastside_Streetcar_Study.pdf |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The study outlined a three-phased eastside loop project that ran from the Broadway Bridge to the Lloyd District, then south through Grand Avenue and [[Oregon Route 99E|Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard]] to Hawthorne Boulevard. A southern crossing back to the west side depended upon whether the new bridge would be constructed, leaving that section undetermined at the time.<ref>{{cite news |last=Leeson |first=Fred |title=Streetcar backers propose loop through Inner Eastside |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 6, 2003 |page=D2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Stern |first1=Henry |last2=Nkrumah |first2=Wade |title=City Council watch |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=June 26, 2003 |page=C2}}</ref>\n\n===Funding and construction===\n\n[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] regional government approved the streetcar extension in July 2006 followed by the city council in September 2007.<ref>{{cite news |last=McGrain |first=Maureen |title=Metro says yes to expansion for streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=July 28, 2006 |url=http://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2006/07/31/story11.html |accessdate=May 20, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"extension-green-light\">{{cite news |last=Mayer |first=James |date=September 7, 2007 |title=Streetcar extension gets green light |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=D1}}</ref> The total cost of the project was $148.8{{nbsp}}million (equivalent to ${{Format price|{{Inflation|US-GDP|148800000|2012}}}} in {{Inflation-year|US-GDP}} dollars), including the cost to purchase additional vehicles.<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\">{{cite report |url=https://www.transit.dot.gov/sites/fta.dot.gov/files/docs/funding/grant-programs/capital-investments/115401/2016-oregon-portland-streetcar-loop-project.pdf |title=Streetcar Loop Project Before-and-After Study (2016) |publisher=[[Federal Transit Administration]] |date=2016 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|19}} Just over half would be paid for with federal funds.<ref name=\"wweek20120822\">{{cite web |title=Slow Ride |url=https://www.wweek.com/portland/article-19584-slow_ride.html |first=Aaron |last=Mesh |date=August 22, 2012 |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |accessdate=August 29, 2012}}</ref> The city council committed to allocating $27{{nbsp}}million of city funds.<ref name=\"extension-green-light\"/> $20{{nbsp}}million from the state, $15.5{{nbsp}}million from a Local Improvement District, and a combination of various other local or regional sources completed the locally matched financing.<ref name=\"factsheetMay2010\">{{cite web |title=Portland Streetcar Loop fact sheet (May 2010) |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |accessdate=August 30, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100821075510/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/pdf/loop_fact_sheet_and_map_201005.pdf |archive-date=August 21, 2010 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> On April 30, 2009, U.S. [[United States Secretary of Transportation|Transportation Secretary]] [[Ray LaHood]] announced $75{{nbsp}}million in federal funding for the project, the full amount that had been requested by Portland. This allocation, secured in large part through the efforts of Oregon [[United States House of Representatives|Representatives]] [[Earl Blumenauer]] and [[Peter DeFazio]], was the largest and final component of the financing plan and meant the project could proceed with construction.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pope |first1=Charles |last2=Rivera |first2=Dylan |title=Feds approve $75 million for streetcar expansion |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005165644/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/04/feds_approve_75_million_for_st.html |archive-date=October 5, 2012 |url-status=unfit}}</ref><ref name=\"Fedsgive\">{{cite news |title=Feds give $75 million for Oregon streetcar |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=April 30, 2009 |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2009/04/27/daily46.html?surround=lfn |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:United Streetcar 10T3 prototype for Portland.jpg|thumb|left|Unveiling of the United Streetcar 10T3 prototype in July 2009]]\n\nIn 2005, the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] approved a spending bill that included $4{{nbsp}}million for a locally produced streetcar vehicle.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |last=Hamilton |first=Don |title=Iron firm forges streetcar desire |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=August 5, 2005 |access-date=April 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331125621/https://www.portlandtribune.com/news/story.php?story_id=31153 |archive-date=March 31, 2012}}</ref> That money went to [[Oregon Iron Works]], which created the subsidiary [[United Streetcar]] upon receiving the contract to build new streetcars for the Portland Streetcar.<ref name=\"streetcarcontract\">{{cite news |author=<!--no by line; staff writer(s)--> |title=Oregon Iron Works gets contract for streetcar |date=January 26, 2007 |newspaper=[[Portland Business Journal]] |url=https://portland.bizjournals.com/portland/stories/2007/01/22/daily45.html |accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> In May 2009, United Streetcar delivered its first prototype to Portland for testing on existing tracks; it was the first U.S.-built streetcar in nearly 60 years.<ref name=\"trib-2009may14\">{{cite news |last=MacKinnon |first=Mary |title=Streetcars soon to be made in Oregon |newspaper=[[Portland Tribune]] |date=May 14, 2009<!--(later re-dated May 13)--> |url=http://portlandtribune.com/component/content/article?id=49492 |accessdate=April 3, 2017}}</ref> That August, the city signed a $20{{nbsp}}million contract to purchase six new streetcars from the manufacturer for the eastside extension.<ref name=\"Oreg14Aug09\">{{cite news |last=Rivera |first=Dylan |title=Portland inks $20 million deal for locally made streetcars |date=August 14, 2009 |newspaper=The Oregonian |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817123910/http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/08/portland_inks_20_million_deal.html |archivedate=17 August 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=June 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGroundbreaking for the Eastside Streetcar Loop project took place on June 25, 2009. The city selected [[Stacy and Witbeck]] to be the project's general contractor and actual construction began the following year.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.opb.org/news/article/construction-begins-eastside-streetcar-loop/ |last=Baer |first=April |title=Construction Begins On Eastside Streetcar Loop |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |date=June 25, 2009 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Across the alignment, crews laid tracks in three- to four-block increments; by February 2010, they were laying tracks on Northeast Grand Avenue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/02/09/streetcar-loop-project/ |title=Streetcar Loop Project |last=Carter |first=Dan |publisher=[[Daily Journal of Commerce]] |date=February 9, 2010 |access-date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> The Broadway Bridge was closed to all traffic to be renovated from July 19 to September 3, 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |title=Portland \u2013 Broadway Bridge will close |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 18, 2010}}</ref> To maintain the existing weight of the bridge (this was necessary to allow the bridge to continue lifting its spans) and simultaneously add tracks, lighter fiber-reinforced concrete replaced the deck.<ref name=\"streetcar work\">{{cite news|last=Rose|first=Joseph |title=Streetcar work shutting down Broadway Bridge |date=July 5, 2010 <!--(July 4 online edition)--> |newspaper=The Oregonian |page=A10 |url=https://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2010/07/streetcar_work_shuts_broadway.html |accessdate=November 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"wrap-up-broadway\">{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/02/18/streetcar-work-almost-finished-on-broadway-bridge/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Streetcar work wraps up on Broadway Bridge |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=February 18, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In the [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]], sections of two former two-way streets\u2014Northwest Lovejoy and Northwest Northrup\u2014were converted into one-way streets following the addition of streetcar tracks. Work completed in this section upon the reopening of the Lovejoy ramp on the west end of the Broadway Bridge in November 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/11/05/pearl-streets-reopen-with-changed-traffic-patterns/ |last=Vorenberg |first=Sue |title=Pearl streets reopen with changed traffic patterns |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=November 5, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> In Southeast Portland, crews built a {{convert|425|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} bridge that led the streetcar to OMSI, the project's eastern terminus.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2010/12/22/portland-streetcar-flyover-bridge-near-omsi/ |last=Carter |first=Dan |title=Portland Streetcar flyover bridge near OMSI |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=December 22, 2010 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Barber Block sunlit with streetcar, 2012.jpg|thumb|right|Car 015 in front of the [[Barber Block]] on Southeast Grand Avenue in 2012]] \n\nIn July 2011, the city council agreed to contractual changes that reduced the number of streetcars on order from six to five.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://djcoregon.com/news/2011/07/20/eastside-streetcar-loop-will-be-delayed-number-of-cars-reduced/ |last=Webber |first=Angela |title=Eastside streetcar loop will be delayed, number of cars reduced |publisher=Daily Journal of Commerce |date=July 20, 2011 |access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> United Streetcar had depended on [[Czech Republic|Czech]] firm [[\u0160koda Transportation|\u0160koda]], which built the system's first streetcars, to build the new streetcars' propulsion system but these failed acceptance testing. Portland officials opted instead to source the propulsion system from [[Wisconsin]]-based [[Rockwell Automation]], but the design was still being developed at the time. They then pursued [[Austria]]n manufacturer Elin to produce a propulsion system for the prototype while they awaited Rockwell. Changes to the propulsion system necessitated changes to the streetcar design in order for the streetcar to accommodate a different form factor; this ultimately delayed the project and raised the cost of manufacturing.<ref name=\"oreg-2011jul19\">{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |newspaper=The Oregonian |date=July 19, 2011 |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |accessdate=September 10, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Opening and extension===\n\nThe {{convert|3.3|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} streetcar extension opened on September 22, 2012, after a five-month-long delay.<ref name=\"PS-History\">{{cite web|title=Streetcar History |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 7, 2015 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203013400/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/33 |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Schmidt |first=Brad |date=July 19, 2011 |title=Portland's $148.3 million eastside streetcar project delayed five months, includes five streetcars instead of six |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/portland/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_1483_million_eastsid.html |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |accessdate=September 17, 2015}}</ref> Its inaugural service, branded the Central Loop Line (abbreviated as CL Line), ran from Southwest Market Street in downtown Portland to OMSI via the Lloyd District.<ref name=\"PS-History\"/> Service along the eastside segment operated with frequencies of 18 minutes instead of the planned 15 minutes due to funding cuts by TriMet and the City of Portland, as well as delays in streetcar delivery from United Streetcar. At the time of opening, fares were $1 following the elimination of the city's [[Fareless Square|Free Rail Zone]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Rose |first=Joseph |authorlink=Joseph Rose (journalist) |date=September 21, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar's eastside loop gets off to hobbled start Saturday |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/commuting/2012/09/portland_streetcars_eastside_l.html |newspaper=The Oregonian |accessdate=September 7, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=October 5, 2012 |title=Portland Streetcar Introduces \u2018Central Loop\u2019 Service |url=http://newsmanager.commpartners.com/aptapt/issues/2012-10-05/3.html |work=Passenger Transport |publisher=[[American Public Transportation Association]] |accessdate=September 8, 2015}}</ref> Approximately 3,200 riders per weekday used the line during the first two weeks of service.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/portland/news/2012/10/31/eastside-streetcar-carrying-the-wait.html |last=Giegerich |first=Andy |title=Eastside streetcar: Carrying the wait |newspaper=Portland Business Journal |date=October 31, 2012 |access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2015, service was extended {{convert|0.9|mi|km}} on the west side from Southwest 10th and Market streets along existing NS Line tracks south to Southwest Moody and Meade streets in the [[South Waterfront, Portland, Oregon|South Waterfront]].<ref name=\"streetcar-loop-fta\"/>{{rp|19}} A new temporary schedule eliminated the name CL Line in favor of two separate routes\u2014A Loop and B Loop. Streetcars began operating across the newly built [[Tilikum Crossing]], but without carrying passengers across the bridge during a two-week transitional \"pre-revenue service\" phase.<ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/> The line was formally re-branded as the Loop Service on September 12, 2015,<ref>{{cite report |url=https://www.oregonmetro.gov/sites/default/files/2018/12/07/RTP-Appendix_G_CTP_20160614.pdf |title=2018 Regional Transportation Plan: Coordinated transportation plan for seniors and people with disabilities |publisher=[[Metro (Oregon regional government)|Metro]] |date=December 6, 2018 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2\u201313}} when the {{convert|1720|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} Tilikum Crossing opened to the public and began permitting streetcars to carry passengers on the route section across the bridge.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://trimet.org/pdfs/pm/Fact-sheets-timelines/TC_2Page_June2014.pdf |title=Tilikum Crossing, Bridge of the People, brings new connections and new options in 2015 |publisher=TriMet |date=June 2014 |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"PS-Loop\"/><ref name=\"PS-History\"/><ref name=\"tilikum-factsheet-2014\">{{cite news |last=Vincent |first=John M. |date=September 8, 2015 |title=Routes, fares change with expanded streetcar service |url=http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |newspaper=[[The Portland Tribune]] |publisher=[[Pamplin Media Group]] |page=A3 |accessdate=August 23, 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151128143529/http://portlandtribune.com/pt/9-news/271906-147003-routes-fares-change-with-expanded-streetcar-service |archivedate=November 28, 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Route==\n[[File:A Lloyd via Peral (21612375879).jpg|thumb|right|An A Loop streetcar on Tilikum Crossing in 2015]]\n[[File:Portland Streetcar car 023 at west end of Broadway Bridge in 2016.jpg|thumb|right|A B Loop streetcar crossing the Broadway Bridge in 2016]]\n\nThe Loop Service forms a {{convert|5.6|mi|km|adj=mid|-long}} [[circle route]] between downtown Portland and the Central Eastside.<ref>{{cite map |url=https://www.transitmap.net/portland-streetcar-2015/ |title=Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |date=2015 |via=transitmap.net}}</ref> A majority of each route runs on one-way single-track. From its original endpoint on Southwest Market Street, the A and B Loops travel northbound through downtown Portland to the Pearl District along NS Line tracks on 10th and 11th avenues.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+10th+%26+Clay/@45.5150904,-122.6838684,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a07f9361b:0x48d11b9676b62d09!8m2!3d45.5144961!4d-122.6849739 |title=SW 10th & Clay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+11th+%26+Clay/@45.5152692,-122.6853204,18z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a1a1bc20dab:0x5353b61f171ae97b!8m2!3d45.5151856!4d-122.6860428 |title=SW 11th & Clay |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The services meet at the intersection of Northwest 10th and Lovejoy where they proceed east towards the Broadway Bridge using the Eastside Loop extension tracks.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NW+9th+%26+Lovejoy/@45.5300511,-122.6789145,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x549509fe395af473:0x1f39de6a4894f631!8m2!3d45.5300534!4d-122.6806308 |title=NW 9th & Lovejoy |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> After crossing the Willamette River on this bridge, the tracks again split, with the A Loop tracks continuing east on Weidler Street and the B Loop tracks on Broadway Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/N+Weidler+%26+Ross/@45.5339555,-122.6694082,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523bc453bf:0xdf7d65ef2959f0dc!8m2!3d45.5344683!4d-122.6694356 |title=N Weidler & Ross |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Broadway+%26+Ross+(Streetcar)/@45.5337533,-122.6705135,17.04z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a7523a89db6d:0x734a73024c507be4!8m2!3d45.53445!4d-122.6695217 |title=NE Broadway & Ross (Streetcar) |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The B Loop turns right on Northeast Grand Avenue and proceeds south through to OMSI.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Grand+%26+Broadway/@45.533741,-122.6611424,17.83z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a74cee1672d9:0x4eb3a0bcd277cf43!8m2!3d45.5347981!4d-122.6605477 |title=NE Grand & Broadway |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right on Northeast 7th Avenue.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Halsey+Southbound/@45.5318626,-122.6610966,17.29z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b333c19a1d:0x22d53ea9dc86a0cb!8m2!3d45.5334298!4d-122.6585944 |title=NE 7th & Halsey Southbound |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> Both tracks intersect MAX Light Rail tracks on Holladay Street.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+7th+%26+Holladay/@45.5299588,-122.6609103,17.08z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0b25eeab5ef:0xa0465a316dd28817!8m2!3d45.5308073!4d-122.6586092 |title=NE 7th & Holladay |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns left on Northeast Oregon street, turns left again in front of the Oregon Convention Center, and heads south on Martin Luther King Jr. Boulevard.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/NE+Oregon+%26+Grand/@45.5286027,-122.6627257,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x5495a0adec0981b1:0xa2326856bed21290!8m2!3d45.5286869!4d-122.6604364 |title=NE Oregon & Grand |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The lines rejoin and enter an overpass at Southeast Harrison Street, which carries them to OMSI and Tilikum Crossing.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SE+Water%2FOMSI+(Streetcar)/@45.5079612,-122.6631697,17.58z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a7236697d75:0x40bba82a7a827677!8m2!3d45.5069508!4d-122.663364 |title=SE Water/OMSI (Streetcar) |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the A and B Loop routes cross the river back to the west side, they re-merge with the NS Line alignment on Southwest Moody Avenue. The tracks turn left onto Southwest River Parkway, which turns into Southwest Harrison Street. They turn right on Southwest 4th Street, then left on Southwest Montgomery Street, and split again at Southwest 5th Avenue. The A Loop crosses PSU's [[Urban Plaza]] diagonally for Southwest Mill Street and the B Loop turns right on Southwest 5th Avenue.<ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/PSU+Urban+Center/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a112fe8f51f:0xb93dc6c9ec4eada!8m2!3d45.5122199!4d-122.6820778 |title=PSU Urban Center |date=April 8, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{google maps |url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+5th+%26+Montgomery/@45.5128647,-122.6834114,17.54z/data=!4m5!3m4!1s0x54950a11485235eb:0x54962f4617846156!8m2!3d45.5117905!4d-122.6812866 |title=SW 5th & Montgomery |access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The A Loop turns right at Southwest 10th Avenue and returns to the intersection of Southwest 10th and Market. The B Loop turns left onto Southwest Market Street and proceeds left until it returns to Southwest 11th and Market. \n\n===Stations===\n\nThe Loop Service serves 52 stations, of which 24 are shared with the NS Line.<ref name=\"maps-schedules\">{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/schedules |title=Maps + Schedules \u2013 Portland Streetcar |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=March 18, 2019}}</ref> Each platform is equipped with a [[ticket vending machine]], [[passenger information system|real-time display]] system, and line information signs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://portlandstreetcar.org/ride-guide/how-to-ride |title=Ride Guide |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=April 1, 2019}}</ref> All stations are [[Accessibility|accessible]] to users with [[Physical disability|limited mobility]].<ref name=\"accessibility-info\">{{cite web |url=http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |title=Accessibility Info |publisher=Portland Streetcar, Inc. |access-date=June 6, 2019 |archive-date=February 1, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120201000132/http://portlandstreetcar.org/node/8 |url-status=unfit}}</ref> Connections to MAX Light Rail are available at 10 stops across the line.<ref name=\"Transit Mall map\">{{cite map |url=https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |title=Portland City Center and Transit Mall |publisher=TriMet |access-date=July 30, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190210193921/https://trimet.org/maps/pdf/citycenter.pdf |archive-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! colspan=2 | Station\n! rowspan=2 | Neighborhood\n! rowspan=2 |Connections and notes<ref name=\"maps-schedules\"/>\n|-\n! A Loop{{br}}(clockwise)\n! B Loop{{br}}(counterclockwise)\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 10th & Northrup\n| rowspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | [[Pearl District, Portland, Oregon|Pearl District]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Northwest 11th & Marshall\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 9th & Lovejoy\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Johnson\n| Northwest 11th & Johnson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Glisan\n| Northwest 11th & Glisan\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Northwest 10th & Couch\n| Northwest 11th & Couch\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[First Regiment Armory Annex|The Armory]], [[Powell's Books|Powell's City of Books]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Alder\n| Southwest 11th & Alder\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\" | [[Downtown Portland, Oregon|Downtown]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Central Library\n| Southwest 11th & Taylor\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Library/Southwest 9th Avenue and Galleria/Southwest 10th Avenue stations|Library and Galleria stations]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Central Library (Portland, Oregon)|Central Library]]\n|-\n| Art Museum\n| Southwest 11th & Jefferson\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland Art Museum]]\n|-\n| Southwest 10th & Clay\n| Southwest 11th & Clay\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| Southwest Park & Mill\n| Southwest Park & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[South Park Blocks]]\n|-\n| \u2014\n| Southwest 5th & Market\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| PSU Urban Center\n| Southwest 5th & Montgomery\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[PSU Urban Center stations]]: [[MAX Green Line|Green]], [[MAX Orange Line|Orange]], [[MAX Yellow Line|Yellow]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Portland State University]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest 3rd & Harrison\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Harrison Street\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest River Parkway & Moody\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}{{br}}Serves [[RiverPlace]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | Southwest Moody & Meade\n| align=\"center\" | [[South Waterfront]]\n| {{rint|portland|NS}}; {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[South Waterfront/Southwest Moody station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Health and Sciences University|OHSU]] Robertson Life Sciences Building, [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" | OMSI\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon|Central Eastside]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[OMSI/Southeast Water station]]: [[MAX Orange Line|Orange Line]]{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Museum of Science and Industry]], [[Tilikum Crossing]]\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Mill\n| Southeast Grand & Mill\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Hawthorne\n| Southeast Grand & Hawthorne\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Taylor\n| Southeast Grand & Taylor\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Morrison\n| Southeast Grand & Morrison\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Southeast MLK & Stark\n| Southeast Grand & Stark\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast MLK & East Burnside\n| Southeast Grand & East Burnside\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Oregon Convention Center\n| Northeast Grand & Hoyt\n| rowspan=\"7\" align=\"center\" | [[Lloyd District, Portland, Oregon|Lloyd District]]\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Convention Center station (TriMet)|Convention Center station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines{{br}}Serves [[Oregon Convention Center]]\n|-\n| Northeast Oregon & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Holladay\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Holladay\n| Northeast Grand & Multnomah\n| {{rint|light rail|link=MAX Light Rail}} [[Northeast 7th Avenue station]]: [[MAX Blue Line|Blue]], [[MAX Green Line|Green]], and [[MAX Red Line|Red]] lines\n|-\n| Northeast 7th & Halsey\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & Grand\n| Northeast Grand & Broadway\n| \u2014\n|-\n| Northeast Weidler & 2nd\n| Northeast Broadway & 2nd\n| \u2014\n|-\n| North Weidler & Ross\n| North Broadway & Ross\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n==Service==\n\nThe Loop Service operates from 5:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on weekdays, from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 11:30&nbsp;p.m. on Saturdays, and from 7:30&nbsp;a.m. to 10:30&nbsp;p.m. on Sundays. Frequencies in each direction range from 15 minutes between 10:00&nbsp;a.m. and 7:00&nbsp;pm on weekdays and Saturdays to 20 minutes on Sundays.<ref name=\"Schedule\">{{cite web |date=August 30, 2015 |title=Streetcar Schedule |url=http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 |publisher=Portland Streetcar |accessdate=September 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Attached KML |display=title,inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150806004043/http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/193 Portland Streetcar Loop Service]\n*[http://www.portlandstreetcar.org/node/3 Portland Streetcar schedule]\n\n{{Portland Transit}}\n{{Streetcars Portland Oregon}}\n{{Portal bar|Oregon|Trains|Transport}}\n\n[[Category:2012 establishments in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Passenger rail transportation in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2012]]\n[[Category:Streetcars in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:TriMet]]\n", "name_user": "Truflip99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRoute:pl", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Loop_Service"}
