{"title_page": "Laverne Cox", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress, reality television star, television producer, and transgender advocate}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2014}}\n<!--Per Wikipedia:Manual of style, use she/her to refer to Laverne Cox throughout her life.-->\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Laverne Cox\n| image         = Laverne Cox by Sachyn Mital cropped.jpg\n| caption       = Cox in July 2014\n| birth_name    = <!-- Do not include birth name, see [[MOS:MULTIPLENAMES]]. -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1972|05|29}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/laverne-cox-explains-why-shes-sharing-historic-third-emmy-nomination-1233682 |title=Laverne Cox Explains Why She Wants to \"Share\" Her Historic Third Emmy Nomination |last=Gardner |first=Chris |date=2019-08-23 |website=hollywoodreporter.com |access-date=2019-09-10}}</ref><ref name=\"birthdate\">{{cite web |url=http://www.playbill.com/features/article/trans-actress-activist-laverne-cox-talks-oitnb-dream-roles-and-startin-322592 |title=Trans Actress-Activist Laverne Cox Talks \"OITNB,\" Dream Roles and Starting a Casting Revolution on Stage and Screen |last=Spaner |first=Whitney |date=15 June 2014 |work=[[Playbill]] |publisher= |access-date=3 June 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n| birth_place   = [[Mobile, Alabama]], U.S.\n| education     = {{unbulleted list|\n  | [[Indiana University Bloomington]]\n  | [[Marymount Manhattan College]]  }}\n| occupation    = {{hlist|Actress|activist}}\n| years_active  = 2000\u2013present\n| relatives     = [[M Lamar]] (twin brother)\n| website       = {{URL|www.lavernecox.com}}\n}}\n'''Laverne Cox''' (born May 29, 1972)<!-- Do not include birth name, see [[MOS:MULTIPLENAMES]]. --> is an American [[actress]] and [[LGBT social movements|LGBTQ+ advocate]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lavernecox.com/bio-2/|title=Laverne Cox Bio|publisher=LaverneCox.com|accessdate=13 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820105221/http://www.lavernecox.com/bio-2/|archivedate=20 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/13/theater/13actout.html|title=Helping Gay Actors Find Themselves Onstage|newspaper=The New York Times|last=Piepenburg|first=Erik|date=12 December 2010|accessdate=12 April 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150612101336/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/13/theater/13actout.html|archivedate=12 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afterelton.com/blog/nycrob/gay-man-transgender-woman-want-to-work-diddy |title=Meet the Gay Man and Transgender Woman Who Want to Work for Diddy |publisher=AfterElton |accessdate=12 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100830102209/http://www.afterelton.com/blog/nycrob/gay-man-transgender-woman-want-to-work-diddy |archivedate=30 August 2010}}</ref> She rose to prominence with her role as [[Sophia Burset]] on the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Orange Is the New Black]]'', becoming the first openly [[transgender]] person to be nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] in any acting category,<ref name=timejuly10>{{cite news |url=http://time.com/2973497/laverne-cox-emmy/ |title=Laverne Cox is the First Transgender Person Nominated for an Emmy \u2013 She Explains Why That Matters |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |first=Aleksandra |last=Gjorgievska |first2=Lily |last2=Rothman |date=July 10, 2014 |accessdate=October 26, 2019|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150201210345/http://time.com/2973497/laverne-cox-emmy/ |archivedate=1 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/laverne-cox-cbs-doubt-pilot-cast-1201431118/| title=Laverne Cox Cast As Transgender Attorney in CBS Legal Drama Pilot| work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]| date=11 February 2015| accessdate=11 February 2015| first=Elizabeth| last=Wagmeister| quote= ... the first openly transgender actor to be nominated for an Emmy ...| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212000146/http://variety.com/2015/tv/news/laverne-cox-cbs-doubt-pilot-cast-1201431118/| archivedate=12 February 2015}}</ref> and the first to be nominated for an Emmy Award since composer [[Angela Morley]] in 1990.<ref name=guardian-morley /> In 2015, she won a Daytime Emmy Award in Outstanding Special Class Special as executive producer for ''Laverne Cox Presents: The T Word'',<ref name=\"Townsend\">{{cite web |last=Townsend |first=Megan |url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/laverne-cox-makes-history-daytime-creative-arts-emmy-win |title=Laverne Cox makes history with Daytime Creative Arts Emmy win |publisher=GLAAD |date=25 April 2015 |accessdate=21 July 2017|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811104618/https://www.glaad.org/blog/laverne-cox-makes-history-daytime-creative-arts-emmy-win |archivedate=11 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Out\">{{cite web |url=http://www.out.com/popnography/2015/4/27/laverne-cox-wins-daytime-emmy |title=Laverne Cox Wins Daytime Emmy |publisher=Out.com |date=27 April 2015 |accessdate=8 July 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160629095709/http://www.out.com/popnography/2015/4/27/laverne-cox-wins-daytime-emmy |archivedate=29 June 2016}}</ref> making her the first openly transgender woman to win the award.<ref name=\"Townsend\"/> In 2017, she became the first transgender person to play a transgender series regular on [[broadcast TV]] as Cameron Wirth on [[CBS]]{{'}}s ''[[Doubt (TV series)|Doubt]]''.<ref name=Heigl>{{cite web|url=http://decoy.tvpassport.com/news/career-revival-katherine-heigl-takes-another-crack-tv-success?subid=national-00001|title=Career revival: Katherine Heigl takes another crack at TV success|last=Spendlove|first=Jacqueline|publisher=TV Media|accessdate=13 February 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819054005/http://decoy.tvpassport.com/news/career-revival-katherine-heigl-takes-another-crack-tv-success?subid=national-00001|archivedate=19 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nCox appeared as a contestant on the first season of [[VH1]]'s [[reality show]] ''[[I Want to Work for Diddy]]'', and co-produced and co-hosted the VH1 makeover television series ''[[TRANSform Me]]''. In April 2014, Cox was honored by [[GLAAD Media Award|GLAAD]] with its [[GLAAD Stephen F. Kolzak Award|Stephen F. Kolzak Award]] for her work as an advocate for the transgender community.<ref name=\"GLAAD.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.glaad.org/releases/laverne-cox-be-honored-25th-annual-glaad-media-awards-los-angeles|title=Laverne Cox to be honored at 25th Annual GLAAD Media Awards in Los Angeles|last=Ferraro|first=Rich|date=31 March 2014|accessdate=31 March 2014|work=[[GLAAD]]| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140423004724/http://www.glaad.org/releases/laverne-cox-be-honored-25th-annual-glaad-media-awards-los-angeles|archivedate=23 April 2014}}</ref> In June 2014, Cox became the first openly transgender person to appear on the cover of [[Time (magazine)|''Time'']] magazine.<ref name=timejuly10 /><ref name=\"thewire.com\">{{cite web |last=Westcott |first=Lucy |url=http://www.thewire.com/culture/2014/05/laverne-cox-is-the-first-transgender-person-on-the-cover-of-time/371798/ |title=Laverne Cox is the First Transgender Person on the Cover of Time |publisher=The Wire |date=29 May 2014 |accessdate=29 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140701061058/http://www.thewire.com/culture/2014/05/laverne-cox-is-the-first-transgender-person-on-the-cover-of-time/371798/ |archivedate=1 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=21 Transgender People Who Influenced American Culture|url=http://time.com/130734/transgender-celebrities-actors-athletes-in-america/|magazine=Time |date=29 May 2014|url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160805093258/http://time.com/130734/transgender-celebrities-actors-athletes-in-america/| archivedate=5 August 2016}}</ref> Cox is the first openly transgender person to appear on the cover of a ''[[Cosmopolitan (magazine)|Cosmopolitan]]'' magazine, with her February 2018 cover on the [[South Africa]]n edition.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/laverne-cox-cosmopolitan-magazine_us_5a660054e4b0e5630071cc41| title=Laverne Cox Makes History as Cosmopolitan's First Transgender Cover Girl|last=Wong|first=Curtis M.|date=22 January 2018|work=Huffington Post|access-date=23 January 2018}}</ref> She is also the first openly transgender person to have a wax figure of herself at [[Madame Tussauds]].<ref name=\"WaxFigure\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-lgbt-cox-idUSKBN0OQ1U420150610|title=Laverne Cox to debut as Madame Tussauds' first transgender wax figure|agency=Reuters|date=10 June 2015| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809122920/http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-lgbt-cox-idUSKBN0OQ1U420150610| archivedate=9 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nLaverne Cox was born a male in [[Mobile, Alabama]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/community/durham-news/article36601533.html |title= Actress Laverne Cox: 'State of emergency' for too many transgender people |last=Sorg |first=Lisa |date= 25 September 2015 |work=[[The News & Observer]] |accessdate= 21 December 2017}}</ref> and was raised by a single mother and grandmother within the [[African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church|AME Zion]] church.<ref name=\"Alternative Radio 2017\">{{cite web|url= https://www.alternativeradio.org/collections/spk_laverne-cox/products/coxl001 | title=Transgender Visibility | publisher=Alternative Radio | date=25 January 2017 | accessdate=2 July 2017 | author=Cox, Laverne | location=Boulder, Colorado | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170819054005/https://www.alternativeradio.org/collections/spk_laverne-cox/products/coxl001 | archivedate=19 August 2017}}</ref> She has an [[identical twin]] brother, [[M Lamar]], who portrayed the pre-[[Transitioning (transgender)|transitioning]] Sophia (as Marcus) in ''Orange is the New Black''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bertstein|first1=Jacob|title=In Their Own Terms \u2013 The Growing Transgender Presence in Pop Culture|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/13/fashion/the-growing-transgender-presence-in-pop-culture.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=21 June 2014|date=12 March 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140328025029/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/03/13/fashion/the-growing-transgender-presence-in-pop-culture.html|archivedate=28 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=salon/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tv.yahoo.com/blogs/tv-news/-orange-is-the-new-black--star-laverne-cox-on-her-twin-brother-s-surprising-role-on-the-series-232519980.html|title='Orange is the New Black' Star Laverne Cox on Her Twin Brother's Surprising Role on the Netflix Series|publisher=Yahoo TV|date=20 August 2013|accessdate=10 January 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140110214135/http://tv.yahoo.com/blogs/tv-news/-orange-is-the-new-black--star-laverne-cox-on-her-twin-brother-s-surprising-role-on-the-series-232519980.html|archivedate=10 January 2014}}</ref> Cox stated she attempted suicide at the age of 11, when she noticed that she had developed feelings for her male classmates and had been bullied for several years for not acting \"the way someone assigned male at birth was supposed to act.\"<ref name=\"Alternative Radio 2017\" /><ref name=wish>{{cite web|last1=Badash|first1=David|title=Laverne Cox: I Have One Wish For America| url=http://www.thenewcivilrightsmovement.com/laverne_cox_i_have_one_wish_for_america| publisher=The New Civil Rights Movement|accessdate=18 August 2014|date=18 August 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819125950/http://www.thenewcivilrightsmovement.com/laverne_cox_i_have_one_wish_for_america| archivedate=19 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hughes|first1=Sarah|title=Laverne Cox: 'We live in a binary world: it can change'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/laverne-cox-we-live-in-a-binary-world-it-can-change-9461564.html|accessdate=21 June 2014|newspaper=The Independent|location=London|date=1 June 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606092520/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/laverne-cox-we-live-in-a-binary-world-it-can-change-9461564.html|archivedate=6 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nShe is a graduate of the [[Alabama School of Fine Arts]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], where she studied creative writing before switching to dance.<ref>{{cite news |author=Interview by Will O'Bryan August 8, 2013 |url=http://www.metroweekly.com/2013/08/laverne-cox-rocks/2/ |title=Laverne Cox Rocks \u2013 Metro Weekly \u2013 Page 2 |publisher=Metroweekly.com |date=8 August 2013 |accessdate=29 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140531104841/http://www.metroweekly.com/2013/08/laverne-cox-rocks/2/ |archivedate=31 May 2014}}</ref> She then studied for two years at [[Indiana University Bloomington]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.indianapolismonthly.com/arts-culture/laverne-cox-details-transgender-journey-iu/ |title=Laverne Cox Details Her Transgender Journey at IU |last1=Zinn |first1=Sarah |date=15 January 2015 |website=indianapolismonthly.com |publisher=Indianapolis Monthly |access-date=27 April 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150508210836/http://www.indianapolismonthly.com/arts-culture/laverne-cox-details-transgender-journey-iu/ |archivedate=8 May 2015}}</ref> before transferring to [[Marymount Manhattan College]] in New York City, where she switched from dancing (specifically classical ballet)<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.backstage.com/interview/emmys-2014-laverne-cox-1-way-fear-helps-performance/|title= Emmys 2014: Laverne Cox on 1 Way Fear Helps Performance|first= Briana|last= Rodriguez|work= backstage.com|date= 1 August 2014|accessdate= 28 June 2015|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150701014455/http://www.backstage.com/interview/emmys-2014-laverne-cox-1-way-fear-helps-performance/|archivedate= 1 July 2015}}</ref> to acting.<ref name=salon>{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2013/07/25/laverne_cox_on_her_orange_is_the_new_black_character_shes_a_survivor/|title=She's a survivor|author=C.J. Dickson|work=[[Salon (website)|Salon.com]]|date=25 July 2013|accessdate=4 August 2013| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130803204429/http://www.salon.com/2013/07/25/laverne_cox_on_her_orange_is_the_new_black_character_shes_a_survivor/| archivedate=3 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/08/05/laverne-cox-shoots-down-host-who-claimed-she-was-born-a-boy/ |title=Watch: Laverne Cox shoots down host who claimed she was 'born a boy' |publisher=Pinknews.co.uk |date=5 August 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808061209/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/08/05/laverne-cox-shoots-down-host-who-claimed-she-was-born-a-boy/ |archivedate=8 August 2014}}</ref> During her first season on ''Orange is the New Black'', she was still appearing at a restaurant on the [[Lower East Side]] as a [[drag queen]] (where she had applied initially to work as a waitress).<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/jun/14/laverne-cox-orange-new-black-transgender|title= Laverne Cox: 'Now I have the money to feminise my face I don't want to. I'm happy' &#124; Life and style &#124; The Guardian|first= Rebecca|last= Nicholson|work= [[The Guardian]]|date= 14 June 2015|accessdate= 28 June 2015|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150701064756/http://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/jun/14/laverne-cox-orange-new-black-transgender|archivedate= 1 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Laverne Cox at Paley Fest Orange Is The New Black.jpg|thumb|upright|right|Laverne Cox at [[PaleyFest]] 2014 representing ''[[Orange is the New Black]]''.]]\nCox appeared as a contestant on the first season of ''I Want to Work for Diddy''; afterwards she was approached by [[VH1]] about show ideas.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.papermag.com/2010/03/reality_bites_laverne_cox_from.php|title=PAPERMAG: Reality Bites: Laverne Cox from VH1's &#60;em&#62;TRANSform Me&#60;/em&#62; |first=Alex|last=Catarinella|work=papermag.com|date=23 March 2010|accessdate=28 June 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701060027/http://www.papermag.com/2010/03/reality_bites_laverne_cox_from.php|archivedate=1 July 2015}}</ref> From that came the makeover television series ''TRANSform Me'', which made Cox the first African-American transgender person to produce and star in her own TV show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/shows/transform_me/cast.jhtml|title=TRANSform Me| publisher=VH1| accessdate=12 April 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120209174823/http://www.vh1.com/shows/transform_me/cast.jhtml|archivedate=9 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"huffingtonpost1\">{{cite web|url=https://huffingtonpost.com/laverne-cox|title=Laverne Cox Bio|work=Huffington Post|accessdate=12 April 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120410153448/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/laverne-cox|archivedate=10 April 2012}}</ref> Both those shows were nominated for a [[GLAAD Media Award]] for outstanding reality program, and when ''Diddy'' won in 2009, Cox accepted the award at the ceremony, giving a speech described by the ''[[San Francisco Sentinel]]'' as \"among the most poignant because [it] reminded us how important it is to tell our stories, all of our stories.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2sbsMZujtvU |title=Laverne Cox and Calpernia Addams at GLAAD Awards 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160425070255/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2sbsMZujtvU|archivedate=25 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.baywindows.com/GLAAD-and-MTPC-Launch-I-AM-Trans-People-Speak-video-series|title=GLAAD and MTPC Launch I AM Trans People Speak video series|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230085720/https://itunes.apple.com/mx/album/rocky-horror-picture-show/id1141483741|archivedate=30 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sanfranciscosentinel.com/?p=26131 |title=On the Carpet at the GLAAD Media Awards |publisher=[[San Francisco Sentinel]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012041030/http://www.sanfranciscosentinel.com/?p=26131 |archivedate=12 October 2013}}</ref> She has also acted in a number of TV shows and films, including ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]'', ''[[Bored to Death]]'', and ''[[Musical Chairs (film)|Musical Chairs]]''.\n\nIn 2013, Cox began her recurring role in the Netflix series ''Orange is the New Black'' as Sophia Burset, a trans woman sent to prison for credit-card fraud. In that year, she stated, \"Sophia is written as a multi-dimensional character who the audience can really empathize with\u2014all of the sudden they're empathizing with a real Trans person. And for Trans folks out there, who need to see representations of people who are like them and of their experiences, that's when it becomes really important.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Douvris|first=Michelle|title=Sitting Down With Orange is the New Black Star Laverne Cox|url=http://emertainmentmonthly.com/2013/11/09/sitting-down-with-orange-is-the-new-black-star-laverne-cox/|publisher=Emertainment Monthly|accessdate=9 November 2013| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131109170321/http://emertainmentmonthly.com/2013/11/09/sitting-down-with-orange-is-the-new-black-star-laverne-cox/| archivedate=9 November 2013}}</ref> Cox's role in ''Orange is the New Black'' provides her a platform to speak on the rights of trans people.\n\nIn January 2014, Cox joined trans woman [[Carmen Carrera]] on [[Katie Couric]]'s syndicated show, ''[[Katie (talk show)|Katie]]''. Couric referred to transgender people as \"transgenders\", and after being rebuffed by Carrera on the subject of her surgeries, specifically what [[Vaginoplasty#Sex reassignment surgery|genital reconstruction]] she had done, turned the same question to Cox. Cox responded,\n\n{{quote|I do feel there is a preoccupation with that. The preoccupation with transition and surgery objectifies trans people. And then we don't get to really deal with the real lived experiences. The reality of trans people's lives is that so often we are targets of violence. We experience discrimination disproportionately to the rest of the community. Our unemployment rate is twice the national average; if you are a trans person of color, that rate is four times the national average. The homicide rate is highest among trans women. If we focus on transition, we don't actually get to talk about those things.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2014/01/07/laverne_cox_artfully_shuts_down_katie_courics_invasive_questions_about_transgender_people/ |title=Laverne Cox flawlessly shuts down Katie Couric's invasive questions about transgender people |work=Salon.com |date=7 January 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301110310/http://www.salon.com/2014/01/07/laverne_cox_artfully_shuts_down_katie_courics_invasive_questions_about_transgender_people/ |archivedate=1 March 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nNews outlets such as ''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'', ''The Huffington Post'', and ''[[Business Insider]]'' covered what was characterized by ''Salon'' writer Katie McDonough as Couric's \"clueless\" and \"invasive\" line of questioning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salon.com/2014/02/06/laverne_cox_i_could_easily_be_a_trans_woman_who_was_fighting_for_her_life/ |title=The post-Katie Couric shift: Laverne Cox tells Salon why the media's so clueless |work=Salon.com |date=6 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140223131103/http://www.salon.com/2014/02/06/laverne_cox_i_could_easily_be_a_trans_woman_who_was_fighting_for_her_life/ |archivedate=23 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nCox was on the cover of the June 9, 2014, issue of ''Time'' and was interviewed for the article \"The Transgender Tipping Point\" by Katy Steinmetz, which ran in that issue and the title of which was also featured on the cover; this makes Cox the first openly transgender person on the cover of ''Time''.<ref name=\"thewire.com\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=Steinmetz |first=Katy |url=http://time.com/135480/transgender-tipping-point/ |title=The Transgender Tipping Point |magazine=TIME |date=29 May 2014 |accessdate=29 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140623043752/http://time.com/135480/transgender-tipping-point/ |archivedate=23 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Myles| last=Tanzer |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/mylestanzer/laverne-cox-is-on-the-cover-of-time-magazine |title=Laverne Cox Is on the Cover of Time Magazine |work=[[BuzzFeed]] |date=29 May 2014 |accessdate=29 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140702022643/http://www.buzzfeed.com/mylestanzer/laverne-cox-is-on-the-cover-of-time-magazine |archivedate=2 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nLater in 2014, Cox became the first openly transgender person to be nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy Award]] in an acting category: Outstanding Guest Actress in a Comedy Series for her role as Sophia Burset in ''Orange Is the New Black''.<ref name=guardian-morley>{{cite news|last=Gaughan |first=Gavin |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2009/jan/23/angela-morley-obituary-wally-stott |title=Obituary: Angela Morley &#124; Television & radio |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=19 July 2014| quote=A transsexual woman, previously known as Wally Stott, she underwent a sex change in 1972. | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140714200037/http://www.theguardian.com/culture/2009/jan/23/angela-morley-obituary-wally-stott | archivedate=14 July 2014| url-status=live|date=January 23, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2014/07/10/emmy-nominees-list/12428631/ |title=2014 Primetime Emmy nominees |publisher=Usatoday.com |date=10 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719042344/http://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2014/07/10/emmy-nominees-list/12428631/ |archivedate=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.extratv.com/2014/07/10/2014-emmy-awards-orange-is-the-new-blacks-laverne-cox-is-first-transgender-nominee/ |title=2014 Emmy Awards: 'Orange is the New Black's' Laverne Cox Is First Transgender Nominee |publisher=ExtraTV.com |date=10 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714152747/http://www.extratv.com/2014/07/10/2014-emmy-awards-orange-is-the-new-blacks-laverne-cox-is-first-transgender-nominee/ |archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref>  She also appeared in [[John Legend]]'s video for the song \"[[You & I (Nobody in the World)]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last=Bendix |first=Trish |url=http://www.afterellen.com/morning-brew-jodie-foster-is-back-on-the-set-of-orange-is-the-new-black/07/2014/ |title=Morning Brew \u2013 Jodie Foster is back on the set of \"Orange is the New Black\" |publisher=AfterEllen.com |date=11 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715042202/http://www.afterellen.com/morning-brew-jodie-foster-is-back-on-the-set-of-orange-is-the-new-black/07/2014/ |archivedate=15 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nCox joined a campaign in 2014 against a Phoenix, Arizona law which allows police to arrest anyone suspected of \"manifesting prostitution,\" and which she feels targets transgender women of color, following the conviction of activist (and transgender woman of color) [[Monica Jones (activist)|Monica Jones]].<ref name=\"pinknews1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/08/06/us-laverne-cox-joins-standwithmonica-campaign-against-phoenix-walking-while-trans-law/ |title=US: Laverne Cox joins #StandWithMonica campaign against Phoenix 'walking while trans' law |publisher=Pinknews.co.uk |accessdate=10 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809181027/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/08/06/us-laverne-cox-joins-standwithmonica-campaign-against-phoenix-walking-while-trans-law/ |archivedate=9 August 2014|date=August 6, 2014 }}</ref> Cox stated, \"All over the country, trans women are targeted simply for being who they are. Laws like this manifestation law really support systematically the idea that girls like me, girls like me and Monica, are less than [others] in this country.\"<ref name=\"pinknews1\"/> Later that year the [[Sylvia Rivera]] Law Project released a video in which Cox read a letter from transgender inmate Synthia China Blast, addressing common issues faced by trans inmates.<ref name=\"Adv26Aug2014\">{{cite news |last=Molloy |first=Parker Marie |url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2014/08/26/laverne-cox-distances-herself-controversial-trans-inmate |title=Laverne Cox Distances Herself From Controversial Trans Inmate |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |date=26 August 2014 |accessdate=13 September 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903064427/http://www.advocate.com/politics/transgender/2014/08/26/laverne-cox-distances-herself-controversial-trans-inmate |archivedate=3 September 2014}}</ref> But when Cox learned that Blast was found guilty of the 1993 rape and murder of 13-year-old Ebony Williams, she wrote on her Tumblr, \"I was not aware of the charges for which she was convicted. If I had been aware of those charges, I would have never agreed to read the letter.\"<ref name=\"Adv26Aug2014\"/>\n\nCox was featured in the annual \"Rebels\" issue of ''[[V (American magazine)|V]]'' in late 2014.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news |last=Sauvalle |first=Julien |url=http://www.out.com/entertainment/popnography/2014/08/22/exclusive-first-look-laverne-cox-honored-v-magazines-rebels |title=Exclusive First Look: Laverne Cox Honored in V magazine's 'Rebels' Issue |work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]] |date=22 August 2014 |accessdate=13 September 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826120424/http://www.out.com/entertainment/popnography/2014/08/22/exclusive-first-look-laverne-cox-honored-v-magazines-rebels |archivedate=August 26, 2014}}</ref> For the issue, V asked celebrities and artists to nominate who they saw as their personal rebels, and [[Natasha Lyonne]] nominated Cox.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> Cox was also on the cover of the October 2014 issue of ''[[Essence (magazine)|Essence]]'' magazine, along with actresses [[Alfre Woodard]], [[Nicole Beharie]], and [[Danai Gurira]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Vulpo |first=Mike |url=http://au.eonline.com/news/573982/laverne-cox-it-feels-so-good-having-a-diverse-cast-on-orange-is-the-new-black |title=Laverne Cox: It Feels \"So Good\" Having a Diverse Cast on Orange Is the New Black |work=E! Online |publisher=[[E!]] |date=28 August 2014 |accessdate=13 September 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230085720/https://itunes.apple.com/mx/album/rocky-horror-picture-show/id1141483741 |archivedate=30 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn October 17, 2014, ''Laverne Cox Presents: The T Word'', an hour-long documentary executive-produced and narrated by Cox, premiered on MTV and Logo simultaneously.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Locker|first1=Melissa|title=Laverne Cox Doc Tackles Transgender Issues For MTV|url=http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2014/10/laverne-cox-t-word-documentary|accessdate=29 October 2014|date=17 October 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021204806/http://www.vanityfair.com/vf-hollywood/2014/10/laverne-cox-t-word-documentary|archivedate=21 October 2014}}</ref>  That same year, Cox was featured on the fifth anniversary cover of ''C\u2606NDY'' magazine along with 13 other transgender women \u2013 [[Janet Mock]], [[Carmen Carrera]], [[Geena Rocero]], [[Isis King]], Gisele Alicea, Leyna Ramous, Dina Marie, Nina Poon, Juliana Huxtable, Niki M'nray, P\u00eache Di, Carmen Xtravaganza ([[House of Xtravaganza]]), and [[Yasmine Petty]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newnownext.com/laverne-cox-carmen-carrera-on-candy-magazine-cover/12/2014/|title=Laverne Cox, Carmen Carrera, Among 14 Trans Stars On \"Candy\" Magazine Cover|work=NewNowNext|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231121619/http://www.newnownext.com/laverne-cox-carmen-carrera-on-candy-magazine-cover/12/2014/|archivedate=31 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Cox won a Daytime Emmy Award in Outstanding Special Class Special as Executive Producer for ''Laverne Cox Presents: The T Word.''<ref name=\"Townsend\"/><ref name=\"Out\"/> This made Cox the first openly transgender woman to win a Daytime Emmy as an Executive Producer; as well, ''The T Word'' is the first trans documentary to win a Daytime Emmy.<ref name=\"Townsend\"/> That year Cox, among others, posed nude for the ''[[Allure (magazine)|Allure]]'' annual \"Nudes\" issue, becoming the first openly transgender actress to do so.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Sasson |first=Eric |url=https://newrepublic.com/article/121653/bruce-jenner-interview-cox-photos-not-transgender-tipping-point |title=Bruce Jenner Interview, Cox Photos Not a Transgender Tipping Point |journal=The New Republic |accessdate=28 April 2015|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428082955/http://www.newrepublic.com/article/121653/bruce-jenner-interview-cox-photos-not-transgender-tipping-point |archivedate=28 April 2015|date=April 27, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nCox is the cover subject for the June 11, 2015 \"totally not-straight issue\" of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', the first issue of the magazine in 15 years to focus exclusively on gay, lesbian, and transgender entertainment.<ref>{{cite news |last=Goldblatt |first=Henry |url=https://ew.com/article/2015/06/11/this-weeks-editors-letter-laverne-surely |title=This week's editor's letter: Laverne, surely |publisher=EW.com |date=11 June 2015 |accessdate=18 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150613081056/http://www.ew.com/article/2015/06/11/this-weeks-editors-letter-laverne-surely |archivedate=13 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, the [[Human Rights Campaign]] released a video in tribute to the victims of the [[2016 Orlando nightclub shooting|2016 Orlando gay nightclub shooting]]; in the video, Cox and others told the stories of the people killed there.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hrc.org/blog/watch-49-celebrities-honor-49-victims-of-orlando-tragedy-in-new-ryan-murphy |title=49 Celebrities Honor 49 Victims of Orlando Tragedy &#124; Human Rights Campaign |publisher=[[Human Rights Campaign]] |date=29 June 2016 |accessdate=30 June 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701211701/http://www.hrc.org/blog/watch-49-celebrities-honor-49-victims-of-orlando-tragedy-in-new-ryan-murphy |archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Rothaus |first=Steve |date=12 June 2016 |title=Pulse Orlando shooting scene a popular LGBT club where employees, patrons 'like family' |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/gay-south-florida/article83301677.html |work=The Miami Herald |access-date=15 June 2016}}</ref>\n[[File:Laverne Cox at L.A.'s Families Belong Together March (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Cox at L.A.'s [[Families Belong Together]] March in June 2018]]\nIn 2017, Cox began her role as transgender attorney Cameron Wirth on ''[[Doubt (TV series)|Doubt]]'' on [[CBS]].<ref name=Heigl/> However, after only two episodes had aired, CBS announced that they were pulling the series from their schedule, leaving the future of the remaining unaired episodes uncertain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2017/02/24/doubt-cancelled-cbs-katherine-heigl-criminal-minds-beyond-borders/ |title=''Doubt'' Canceled After 2 Episodes, to Be Replaced by ''Beyond Borders'' |last=Nemetz |first=Dan |publisher=TVLine |date=24 February 2017 |accessdate=24 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225084527/http://tvline.com/2017/02/24/doubt-cancelled-cbs-katherine-heigl-criminal-minds-beyond-borders/ |archivedate=25 February 2017}}</ref> It was the first official cancellation of the [[2016\u201317 United States network television schedule|2016\u201317 season]], following weak viewership. CBS later announced that the remaining 11 episodes would be broadcast on Saturday, beginning July 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2017/06/20/doubt-season-1-episodes-air-date-schedule-cancelled/|title=Doubt Update: CBS to Air Cancelled Drama's 11 Remaining Episodes| publisher=TVLine| first=Michael| last=Ausiello| date=20 June 2017|accessdate=20 June 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170621004142/http://tvline.com/2017/06/20/doubt-season-1-episodes-air-date-schedule-cancelled/|archivedate=21 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nCox was nominated in 2017 for a [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series]] for her role in ''Orange Is the New Black''.<ref name=\"Orange\">{{cite web |last=Webb |first=Matt |url=http://tvline.com/2017/07/13/2017-emmy-nominations-list-awards/ |title=2017 Emmy Nominations List: Actor and Actress Nominees |publisher=TVLine |date=13 July 2017 |accessdate=21 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721181423/http://tvline.com/2017/07/13/2017-emmy-nominations-list-awards/ |archivedate=21 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nAlso in 2017, Cox collaborated with the [[ACLU]], [[Zackary Drucker]], [[Molly Crabapple]], and [[Kim Boekbinder]], in making a video about transgender history and resistance, called \"Time Marches Forward & So Do We\", which Cox narrated.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://time.com/4894647/trans-transgender-rights-video/ |title=Transgender Rights History Told by Laverne Cox: Watch VIDEO |magazine=Time.com |date=10 August 2017 |accessdate=11 August 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811010415/http://time.com/4894647/trans-transgender-rights-video/ |archivedate=11 August 2017}}</ref>  That year Cox became one of the four faces of the fall campaign for the [[Ivy Park]] line of clothing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://latimes.com/fashion/la-ig-laverne-cox-beyonce-ivy-park-20170906-htmlstory.html |title=Laverne Cox takes a starring role in Beyonc\u00e9's new Ivy Park campaign |newspaper=LA Times |date=6 September 2017 |accessdate=15 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nCox was featured in [[Taylor Swift]]'s \"You Need to Calm Down\" music video, which was released June 17, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/taylor-swift-you-need-to-calm-down-video-celebrity-appearances|title=Taylor Swift's \"You Need to Calm Down\" Video Will Have a Star-Studded Cast|last=Nast|first=Cond\u00e9|website=Teen Vogue|language=en|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>\n\nShe was one of fifteen women chosen by guest editor [[Meghan, Duchess of Sussex]] to appear on the cover of the September 2019 issue of [[British Vogue|British ''Vogue'']]; this made Cox the first openly transgender woman to appear on the cover of British ''Vogue''.<ref name=\"IT-2019-07-31\">{{cite web |title=Meghan Markle puts Sin\u00e9ad Burke on the cover of Vogue's September issue |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/fashion/meghan-markle-puts-sin\u00e9ad-burke-on-the-cover-of-vogue-s-september-issue-1.3970604 |website=The Irish Times |accessdate=31 July 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"ind-29jul2019\">{{cite news |last1=Barr |first1=Sabrina |title=Meghan Markle: Jameela Jamil, Laverne Cox and Gemma Chan react to appearing on cover of British Vogue |url=https://news.yahoo.com/meghan-markle-jameela-jamil-laverne-091736640.html |accessdate=July 29, 2019 |work=[[The Independent]] |publisher=[[Yahoo! News]] |date=July 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://theglowup.theroot.com/thanks-to-meghan-markle-laverne-cox-is-the-1st-trans-w-1836855649 |title=Thanks to Meghan Markle, Laverne Cox Is the 1st Trans Woman to Appear on the Cover of British Vogue |publisher=Theglowup.theroot.com |date=2019-07-25 |accessdate=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, Cox brought [[ACLU]] attorney [[Chase Strangio]] as her date to the [[71st Primetime Emmy Awards|2019 Emmy Awards]], and carried a custom rainbow clutch featuring the phrases \"Oct 8\", \"Title VII\", and \"Supreme Court\". This action was in reference to the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] case ''[[R.G. & G.R. Harris Funeral Homes Inc. v. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission]]'', in which Strangio was one of the lawyers representing Aimee Stephens, a trans woman who was fired from her job at a funeral home. Cox and Strangio spoke to reporters on the [[red carpet]] about the upcoming court case.<ref name=\"bustle-22sep2019\">{{cite web |last1=Fratti |first1=Karen |title=Laverne Cox's 2019 Emmys Date Is Bringing Attention To A Vital Court Case |url=https://www.bustle.com/p/laverne-coxs-2019-emmys-date-is-bringing-attention-to-a-vital-court-case-18793157 |website=[[Bustle (website)|Bustle]] |accessdate=October 16, 2019 |date=September 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"vf-23sep2019\">{{cite magazine |last1=Vanderhoof |first1=Erin |title=Emmys 2019: Laverne Cox's Political Rainbow Purse Had a Secret Message |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2019/09/emmys-2019-laverne-cox-rainbow-purse |accessdate=October 16, 2019 |magazine=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]] |date=September 23, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"usa-22sep2019\">{{cite news |last1=McDermott |first1=Maeve |title=Emmys 2019: Laverne Cox's clutch has an important pro-LGBTQ message |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/celebrities/2019/09/22/emmys-2019-laverne-coxs-clutch-has-important-pro-lgbtq-message/2414270001/ |accessdate=October 16, 2019 |work=[[USA Today]] |date=September 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Impact ==\nLaverne Cox has been noted by her LGBT peers, and many others, for being a [[wikt:trailblazer|trailblazer]] for the transgender community,<ref>{{cite web |last=Nudd |first=Tim |url=http://www.people.com/article/laverne-cox-honors-stonewall-logotv-trailblazers |title=Orange is the New Black's Laverne Cox Honors the Legacy of Stonewall at Logo's Trailblazer Awards - LOGO, Orange is the New Black |magazine=[[People (magazine)|People]] |date=26 June 2014 |accessdate=18 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618194337/http://www.people.com/article/laverne-cox-honors-stonewall-logotv-trailblazers |archivedate=18 June 2015}}</ref> and has won numerous awards for her activist approach in spreading awareness. Her impact and prominence in the media has led to a growing conversation about transgender culture,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/06/06/laverne-cox-and-the-state-of-trans-representation-in-pop-culture |title=Laverne Cox and the State of Trans Representation in Pop Culture |publisher=US News |date=6 June 2014 |accessdate=18 June 2015|url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619061556/http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/06/06/laverne-cox-and-the-state-of-trans-representation-in-pop-culture |archivedate=19 June 2015}}</ref> specifically transgender women, and how being transgender intersects with one's race.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2014/2/24/laverne-cox-trans-event/ |title=Actress Laverne Cox Discusses Identity, Trans Issues &#124; News &#124; The Harvard Crimson |publisher=[[Harvard Crimson]] |date=24 February 2014 |accessdate=18 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618193432/http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2014/2/24/laverne-cox-trans-event/ |archivedate=18 June 2018}}</ref> She is the first openly transgender person to be on the cover of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine,<ref name=\"timejuly10\" /> be nominated for a [[Primetime Emmy]],<ref name=\":1\" /> and have a wax work in Madame Tussauds,<ref name=\"WaxFigure\" /> as well as the first openly transgender woman to win a Daytime Emmy as an [[Executive Producer]].<ref name=\"townsend1\"/> In May 2016, Cox was awarded an [[honorary degree|Honorary Doctorate]] from [[The New School]] in [[New York City]] for her progressive work in the fight for [[gender equality]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.newschool.edu/news/2016/05/commencement-2016-honorary-degree-recipients/|title=Commencement 2016: Get To Know The Honorary Degree Recipients|work=blogs.newschool.edu| date=3 May 2016|accessdate=23 May 2016| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518230850/http://blogs.newschool.edu/news/2016/05/commencement-2016-honorary-degree-recipients/|archivedate=18 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n* 2013 \u2013 Anti-Violence Project 2013 Courage Award honoree<ref>{{cite web|last=Vieira|first=Meredith|title=Laverne Cox and her Transgender Transformation (OVERSHARE EP 3)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t_znTP-sWi8&t=0m27s|work=Lives with Meredith Vieira|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=21 November 2013| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610171512/http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=t_znTP-sWi8&t=0m27s|archivedate=10 June 2014}}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 Reader's Choice Award at ''[[Out Magazine]]''{{'}}s OUT100 Gala, honoring the magazine's selection of 2013's 100 \"most compelling people of the year.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.out.com/out-exclusives/out100-2013/2013/11/05/laverne-cox-actress-activist-trans-orange-black |title=Reader's Choice Award |publisher=Out.com |accessdate=29 June 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140813143320/http://www.out.com/out-exclusives/out100-2013/2013/11/05/laverne-cox-actress-activist-trans-orange-black |archivedate=13 August 2014}}</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 Woman of the Year by ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://huffingtonpost.com/2014/11/05/laverne-cox-glamour-magazine_n_6109726.html|title=Breaking News and Opinion on The Huffington Post|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=7 November 2014|date=5 November 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141107204616/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/11/05/laverne-cox-glamour-magazine_n_6109726.html| archivedate=7 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.glamour.com/inspired/women-of-the-year/2014/laverne-cox|title=Laverne Cox Is a Glamour Woman of the Year for 2014: Glamour.com|work=[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]|accessdate=7 November 2014| url-status=live| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106142414/http://www.glamour.com/inspired/women-of-the-year/2014/laverne-cox|archivedate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 Included in the annual Root 100; this list honors \"standout black leaders, innovators and culture shapers\" aged 45 and younger.<ref>{{cite news |last=Juro |first=Rebecca |url=http://www.advocate.com/politics/media/2014/09/11/root-100-recognizes-african-american-lgbt-luminaries |title=Root 100 Recognizes African-American LGBT Luminaries |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |date=11 September 2014 |accessdate=13 September 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912002314/http://www.advocate.com/politics/media/2014/09/11/root-100-recognizes-african-american-lgbt-luminaries |archivedate=12 September 2014}}</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 Topped the British newspaper ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s third annual World Pride Power List, which ranks the world's most influential LGBT people.<ref>{{cite web |author=Materville Studios \u2013 Host of Windy City Times |url=http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/Gay-team-makes-history-Laverne-Cox-tops-world-list/48244.html |title=Gay team makes history; Laverne Cox tops world list \u2013 520 \u2013 Gay Lesbian Bi Trans News Archive |work=Windy City Times |date=8 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714233944/http://www.windycitymediagroup.com/lgbt/Gay-team-makes-history-Laverne-Cox-tops-world-list/48244.html |archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 [[Stephen F. Kolzak Award]] from [[GLAAD]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/04/13/watch-ellen-page-presents-orange-is-the-new-black-star-laverne-cox-with-glaad-award/ |title=Watch: Ellen Page presents 'Orange is the New Black' star Laverne Cox with GLAAD award |publisher=Pinknews.co.uk |date=13 April 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140724074314/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/04/13/watch-ellen-page-presents-orange-is-the-new-black-star-laverne-cox-with-glaad-award/ |archivedate=24 July 2014}}</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 Named to the EBONY Power 100 list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naacpldf.org/press-release/ebony-magazine-unveils-its-2014-ebony-power-100-list|title=EBONY Magazine Unveils Its 2014 EBONY Power 100 List \u2013 NAACP LDF|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219232734/http://www.naacpldf.org/press-release/ebony-magazine-unveils-its-2014-ebony-power-100-list|archivedate=19 December 2014}}</ref>\n* 2015 \u2013 Named to the 2015 OUT Power 50 List.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.out.com/power-50-2015 |title=Power 50 2015 |work=Out Magazine |date=14 April 2015 |accessdate=22 April 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150417221651/http://www.out.com/power-50-2015 |archivedate=17 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015 \u2013 Included in the ''[[People (magazine)|People]]'' World's Most Beautiful Women List.<ref>{{cite web |last=McDonald |first=James |url=http://www.out.com/popnography/2015/4/22/laverne-cox-one-people-magazines-most-beautiful-women |title=Laverne Cox Is One of People's Most Beautiful Women |work=Out Magazine |date=30 March 2015 |accessdate=22 April 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150424155724/http://www.out.com/popnography/2015/4/22/laverne-cox-one-people-magazines-most-beautiful-women |archivedate=24 April 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015 \u2013 Three Twins Ice Cream in San Francisco renamed its chocolate orange confetti ice cream Laverne Cox's Chocolate Orange is the New Black for Pride weekend.<ref>{{cite web |first=Trudy| last=Ring |url=http://www.advocate.com/pride/2015/06/17/laverne-cox-gets-ice-cream-flavor-named-her-pride |title=Laverne Cox Gets Ice Cream Flavor Named for Her for Pride |publisher=Advocate.com |date=31 July 2014 | accessdate=18 June 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618194115/http://www.advocate.com/pride/2015/06/17/laverne-cox-gets-ice-cream-flavor-named-her-pride |archivedate=18 June 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015 \u2013 Named in the 2015 ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' 100 Most Influential People List; her entry was written by [[Jazz Jennings]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://time.com/3822970/laverne-cox-2015-time-100/ |title=Laverne Cox by Jazz Jennings: TIME 100 |magazine=Time.com |date=16 April 2015 |accessdate=22 April 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150422022408/http://time.com/3822970/laverne-cox-2015-time-100/ |archivedate=22 April 2015 }}</ref>\n* 2015 \u2013 Named by [[Forum for Equality]] as one of their 31 Icons of the [[LGBT History Month]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Lazin |first=Malcolm |url=http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2015/08/20/op-ed-here-are-31-icons-2015s-gay-history-month |title=Op-ed: Here Are the 31 Icons of 2015's Gay History Month |publisher=Advocate.com |date=20 August 2015 |accessdate=21 August 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821113613/http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2015/08/20/op-ed-here-are-31-icons-2015s-gay-history-month |archivedate=21 August 2015}}</ref>\n* 2015 \u2013 Winner of a Daytime Emmy Award in Outstanding Special Class Special as Executive Producer for ''Laverne Cox Presents: The T Word.''<ref name=\"townsend1\">{{cite web |last=Townsend |first=Megan |url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/laverne-cox-makes-history-daytime-creative-arts-emmy-win |title=Laverne Cox makes history with Daytime Creative Arts Emmy win |publisher=GLAAD |date=25 April 2015 |accessdate=21 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230085720/https://itunes.apple.com/mx/album/rocky-horror-picture-show/id1141483741 |archivedate=30 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Out\"/> This made Cox the first openly transgender woman to win a Daytime Emmy as an Executive Producer; as well, ''The T Word'' is the first trans documentary to win a Daytime Emmy.<ref name=\"townsend1\"/>\n* 2016 \u2014 Awarded Honorary Doctorate from [[The New School]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newschool.edu/pressroom/pressreleases/2016/commencement2016.htm |title=LAVERNE COX, DIANE VON FURSTENBERG, DERAY MCKESSON NAMED HONORARY DEGREE RECIPIENTS BY THE NEW SCHOOL |date=31 March 2016}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 Named to the 2017 OUT Power 50 List.<ref>{{cite web |author=By Out.com Editors |url=https://www.out.com/power-50/2017/7/17/power50-2017 |title=Power 50 2017 |work=Out Magazine |accessdate=21 July 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170727060131/https://www.out.com/power-50/2017/7/17/power50-2017 |archivedate=27 July 2017|date=July 19, 2017 }}</ref>\n* 2018 \u2014 Received the Claire Skiffington Vanguard Award from [[Transgender Law Center]]. The award recognizes transgender community members who have been part of the movement's vanguard.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://transgenderlawcenter.org/archives/14364|title=TLC announces Laverne Cox as SPARK! 2018 Honoree| date=20 October 2018| accessdate=27 October 2018| publisher=[[Transgender Law Center]]}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2000\n| ''Betty Anderson''\n| Deirdre\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''{{sortname|The|Kings of Brooklyn|nolink=1}}''\n| Girl\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''All Night''\n| Layla\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Uncle Stephanie''\n| Stephanie\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''Bronx Paradise''\n| Hooker\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''Carla''\n| Cinnamon\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Musical Chairs (film)|Musical Chairs]]''\n| Chantelle\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''Migraine''\n| Lola\n| Short film\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''{{sortname|The|Exhibitionists|nolink=1}}''\n| Blithe Stargazer\n|\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[36 Saints]]''\n| Genesuis\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Grand Street''\n| Chardonnay\n|\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Laverne Cox Presents: The T Word''\n| Herself\n|[[Daytime Emmy Awards|Daytime Emmy Awards for Outstanding Special Class Special]] (2015)<br />Nominated - [[GLAAD Media Awards|GLAAD Media Award for Outstanding Documentary]] (2015)\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Grandma (film)|Grandma]]''\n|Deathy\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Freak Show (film)|Freak Show]]''\n| Felicia\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Can You Keep a Secret? (film)|Can You Keep a Secret?]]''\n| Cybill\n| \n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Charlie's Angels (2019 film)|Charlie's Angels]]''\n| Bomb Instructor\n|\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Bad Hair (2020 film)|Bad Hair]]''\n| Virgie\n| \n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Promising Young Woman]]''\n| Gail\n|\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''Disclosure: Trans Lives on Screen''\n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Jolt (film)|Jolt]]''\n| Detective Nevin\n|Post-production\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Law & Order: Special Victims Unit]]''\n| Candace\n| Episode: \"Closet\"\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[I Want to Work for Diddy (season 1)|I Want to Work for Diddy]]''\n| Herself\n| 6 episodes\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[Law & Order]]''\n| Minnie\n| Episode: \"Sweetie\"\n|-\n|