[Category:American Dad! (season 17) episodes]]\n", "name_user": "Yay Dad", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEpisodes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Dad!_(season_17)"}
{"title_page": "Henrietta Stewart", "text_new": "{{short description|Scottish courtier}}\n{{Distinguish|Henrietta Stuart}}\n[[File:Huntly Castle, detail of front inscriptions.jpg|thumb|right|The names of Henrietta and her husband are carved across the fa\u00e7ade of [[Huntly Castle]].]]\n'''Henrietta Stewart''' (1573\u20131642), was a Scottish courtier. She was the influential favourite of the queen of Scotland, [[Anne of Denmark]]. \n\n==Life==\nHenrietta Stewart was the daughter of [[Esm\u00e9 Stewart, 1st Duke of Lennox ]] and Catherine de Balsac. Henrietta, her sister [[Marie Stewart, Countess of Mar|Marie]] and her brother [[Ludovic Stewart, 2nd Duke of Lennox|Ludovic]] came back to Scotland from France in 1587.\n\nOn 21 July 1588, Henrietta married [[George Gordon, 1st Marquess of Huntly]], then [[Earl of Huntly]], at [[Holyroodhouse]]. [[James VI of Scotland]] wrote a masque to be performed at the wedding.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/newpoemsbyjamesi00jameiala/page/46 Allan Westcott, ''New poems by James I of England: from a hitherto unpublished manuscript'' (Columbia University Press, 1911), pp. 47\u201352]: Jane Rickard, ''Authorship and Authority in the writings of James VI and I'' (Manchester, 2007), pp. 54-56: Rhodes Dunlap, 'King James's Own Masque', ''Philological Quarterly'', 41 (1962), pp. 249-56.</ref> The wedding celebrations at [[Holyroodhouse]] involving \"plays and masquerades\" lasted two or three days. [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]] gave her a chain of pearls and hair garnishings.<ref>''HMC Calendar of the Manuscripts of the Marquess of Salisbury at Hatfield House'', vol. 3 (London, 1889), pp. 336 no. 691, 341 no. 709.</ref> The king sent requests to lairds, like Murray of [[Abercairny]], for \"venison, wild fowls, fed capons\" for the feast.<ref>''HMC 3rd Report: Moray'' (London, 1872), p. 419.</ref> Before the wedding the couple were made to declare their (Protestant) faith, without which the minister John Craig would not declare the banns.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 9 (Edinburgh, 1915), pp. 583, 587.</ref>\n\nMarie Stewart became a lady-in-waiting in the household of [[Anne of Denmark]] in December 1590 at Henrietta's request, which increased Henrietta's access at court, and she married the [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|Earl of Mar]] in December 1592.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 429.</ref> Their younger sister Gabrielle was a nun in France at Glatigny, but a scheme for her to marry Hugh Montgomerie, 5th [[Earl of Eglinton]] in 1598 came to nothing.<ref>''Scots Peerage'' vol. 5 (1908), p. 356: William Fraser, ''Memorials of the Montgomeries Earls of Eglinton'', vol 2 (Edinburgh, 1859), no. 201, now NRS GD3/2/15/10.</ref>\n\nIn February 1593 King James came north to punish and subdue the earls of Huntly, Angus, and Erroll for plotting on behalf of the Catholic faith but they went into hiding. Henrieta and [[Elizabeth Douglas, Countess of Erroll]] came to him at Aberdeen and he allowed them to keep their houses and estates.<ref>''Historie and Life of King James the Sext'' (Edinburgh, 1830), p. 268.</ref>\n\nEventually, Henrietta came to be a favourite of the queen, and exerted an influence over her which became controversial.  Henrietta was known to be a fervent Catholic, and the friendship between her and Anne was politically sensitive and developed into a cause for conflict between the king and the queen.  It also brought Queen Anne negative publicity and exposed her to criticism from the Scottish church.  Henrietta Stewart is speculated to have played a part in Queen Anne's rumoured secret Catholic conversion. \n\nHenrietta was able to further her husband's cause at court even when he was forfeited, except in June 1594 when James expressly forbade her attendance. She defied his order and visited Anne of Denmark at [[Holyroodhouse]] in \"base array\", disguised as a servant, on a day when the king had gone to [[Stirling Castle]] to see the building work on the new Chapel Royal.<ref>Grant (2017), p. 71: ''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 362\u20133.</ref>\n\nIn 1596 pressure was exerted on her and her husband to convert from Catholicism by taking away her eldest son [[George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly|Lord Gordon]]. He was to be brought up and court and sent to the [[University of Edinburgh]] as a pupil of [[Robert Rollock]]. Anne of Denmark bought him clothes including a velvet coat and a belt with a little dagger.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), pp. 162, 183, 359, 388.</ref> [[David Moysie]] wrote that Henrietta's representations to a [[Parliament of Scotland|Convention of the Estates]] were twice rejected.<ref>David Moysie, [https://archive.org/stream/memoirsaffairss01denngoog#page/n166/mode/2up ''Memoirs of the Affairs of Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1830), p. 127].</ref> On 19 October 1596 Henrietta's representatives presented her signed seven-point offer to the Synod of the Presbyteries of [[Diocese of Moray|Moray]] at [[Elgin, Moray|Elgin]] on behalf of her husband, undertaking to assist the Protestant ministry and to eject Jesuits from his company.<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), pp. 358, 360-1.</ref>\n\nShe was a godmother to [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia|Princess Elizabeth]] at her christening on 28 November 1596, and held [[Charles I of England|Prince Charles]] at his christening in 1600.<ref>Grant (2017), p. 71.</ref> It was noted in November 1600 that she was \"chiefest\" in favour with Anna of Denmark.<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland: 1597-1603'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 730.</ref>\n\nHer name is carved in stone across the upper storey of [[Huntly Castle]] in 20-inch letters, in equal prominence to her husband's.<ref>Grant (2017), p. 72.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHer children included:\n* Anne Gordon, who married [[James Stuart, 3rd Earl of Moray]].\n* Elizabeth Gordon, who married [[Alexander Livingston, 2nd Earl of Linlithgow]] in 1611.\n* Mary Gordon, who married [[William Douglas, 1st Marquess of Douglas]].\n* [[George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly]]\n* Jean Gordon, who married [[Claud Hamilton, 2nd Baron Hamilton of Strabane]]\n* John Gordon, [[Viscount of Melgum]].\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n* Ruth Grant, in Elizabeth L. Ewan, Sue Innes, Sian Reynolds, Rose Pipes, ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=Zs6qBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA15&dq=Lady+Henrietta+Stewart+anne+of+denmark&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjF55KmuJThAhXD86YKHVTmDPIQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Lady%20Henrietta%20Stewart%20anne%20of%20denmark&f=false Biographical Dictionary of Scottish Women]'' (Edinburgh, 2018), pp. 411\u2013412.\n* Susan Dunn-Hensley, ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=DaQ5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=Henrietta+huntley+anne+of+denmark&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjCzvnAuZThAhWwyqYKHWI5ClkQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Henrietta%20huntley%20anne%20of%20denmark&f=false Anna of Denmark and Henrietta Maria: Virgins, Witches, and Catholic Queens]''\n* Ruth Grant, 'Friendship, politics and religion: George Gordon, Sixth Earl of Huntly and King James VI, 1581\u20131595', Miles Kerr-Peterson & Steven Reid, ''James VI and Noble Power'' (Abingdon, 2017), pp. 57\u201390.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Henrietta}}\n[[Category:1573 births]]\n[[Category:1642 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish ladies-in-waiting]]\n[[Category:Scottish royal favourites]]\n[[Category:Marchionesses]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:Scottish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Scottish countesses|#Huntly]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Scottish courtier}}\n{{Distinguish|Henrietta Stuart}}\n[[File:Huntly Castle, detail of front inscriptions.jpg|thumb|right|The names of Henrietta and her husband are carved across the fa\u00e7ade of [[Huntly Castle]].]]\n'''Henrietta Stewart''' (1573\u20131642), was a Scottish courtier. She was the influential favourite of the queen of Scotland, [[Anne of Denmark]]. \n\n==Life==\nHenrietta Stewart was the daughter of [[Esm\u00e9 Stewart, 1st Duke of Lennox ]] and Catherine de Balsac. Henrietta, her sister [[Marie Stewart, Countess of Mar|Marie]] and her brother [[Ludovic Stewart, 2nd Duke of Lennox|Ludovic]] came back to Scotland from France in 1587.\n\nOn 21 July 1588, Henrietta married [[George Gordon, 1st Marquess of Huntly]] at [[Holyroodhouse]]. [[James VI of Scotland]] wrote a masque to be performed at the wedding.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/newpoemsbyjamesi00jameiala/page/46 Allan Westcott, ''New poems by James I of England: from a hitherto unpublished manuscript'' (Columbia University Press, 1911), pp. 47\u201352]: Jane Rickard, ''Authorship and Authority in the writings of James VI and I'' (Manchester, 2007), pp. 54-56: Rhodes Dunlap, 'King James's Own Masque', ''Philological Quarterly'', 41 (1962), pp. 249-56.</ref> The wedding celebrations at [[Holyroodhouse]] involving \"plays and masquerades\" lasted two or three days. [[Francis Stewart, 5th Earl of Bothwell]] gave her a chain of pearls and hair garnishings.<ref>''HMC Calendar of the Manuscripts of the Marquess of Salisbury at Hatfield House'', vol. 3 (London, 1889), pp. 336 no. 691, 341 no. 709.</ref> The king sent requests to lairds, like Murray of [[Abercairny]], for \"venison, wild fowls, fed capons\" for the feast.<ref>''HMC 3rd Report: Moray'' (London, 1872), p. 419.</ref> Before the wedding the couple were made to declare their (Protestant) faith, without which the minister John Craig would not declare the banns.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 9 (Edinburgh, 1915), pp. 583, 587.</ref>\n\nMarie Stewart became a lady-in-waiting in the household of [[Anne of Denmark]] in December 1590 at Henrietta's request, which increased Henrietta's access at court, and she married the [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|Earl of Mar]] in December 1592.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 429.</ref> Their younger sister Gabrielle was a nun in France at Glatigny, but a scheme for her to marry Hugh Montgomerie, 5th [[Earl of Eglinton]] in 1598 came to nothing.<ref>''Scots Peerage'' vol. 5 (1908), p. 356: William Fraser, ''Memorials of the Montgomeries Earls of Eglinton'', vol 2 (Edinburgh, 1859), no. 201, now NRS GD3/2/15/10.</ref>\n\nIn February 1593 King James came north to punish and subdue the earls of Huntly, Angus, and Erroll for plotting on behalf of the Catholic faith but they went into hiding. Henrieta and [[Elizabeth Douglas, Countess of Erroll]] came to him at Aberdeen and he allowed them to keep their houses and estates.<ref>''Historie and Life of King James the Sext'' (Edinburgh, 1830), p. 268.</ref>\n\nEventually, Henrietta came to be a favourite of the queen, and exerted an influence over her which became controversial.  Henrietta was known to be a fervent Catholic, and the friendship between her and Anne was politically sensitive and developed into a cause for conflict between the king and the queen.  It also brought Queen Anne negative publicity and exposed her to criticism from the Scottish church.  Henrietta Stewart is speculated to have played a part in Queen Anne's rumoured secret Catholic conversion. \n\nHenrietta was able to further her husband's cause at court even when he was forfeited, except in June 1594 when James expressly forbade her attendance. She defied his order and visited Anne of Denmark at [[Holyroodhouse]] in \"base array\", disguised as a servant, on a day when the king had gone to [[Stirling Castle]] to see the building work on the new Chapel Royal.<ref>Grant (2017), p. 71: ''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 11 (Edinburgh, 1936), pp. 362\u20133.</ref>\n\nIn 1596 pressure was exerted on her and her husband to convert from Catholicism by taking away her eldest son [[George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly|Lord Gordon]]. He was to be brought up and court and sent to the [[University of Edinburgh]] as a pupil of [[Robert Rollock]]. Anne of Denmark bought him clothes including a velvet coat and a belt with a little dagger.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), pp. 162, 183, 359, 388.</ref> [[David Moysie]] wrote that Henrietta's representations to a [[Parliament of Scotland|Convention of the Estates]] were twice rejected.<ref>David Moysie, [https://archive.org/stream/memoirsaffairss01denngoog#page/n166/mode/2up ''Memoirs of the Affairs of Scotland'' (Edinburgh, 1830), p. 127].</ref> On 19 October 1596 Henrietta's representatives presented her signed seven-point offer to the Synod of the Presbyteries of [[Diocese of Moray|Moray]] at [[Elgin, Moray|Elgin]] on behalf of her husband, undertaking to assist the Protestant ministry and to eject Jesuits from his company.<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland'', vol. 12 (Edinburgh, 1952), pp. 358, 360-1.</ref>\n\nShe was a godmother to [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia|Princess Elizabeth]] at her christening on 28 November 1596, and held [[Charles I of England|Prince Charles]] at his christening in 1600.<ref>Grant (2017), p. 71.</ref> It was noted in November 1600 that she was \"chiefest\" in favour with Anna of Denmark.<ref>''Calendar of State Papers Scotland: 1597-1603'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 730.</ref>\n\nHer name is carved in stone across the upper storey of [[Huntly Castle]] in 20-inch letters, in equal prominence to her husband's.<ref>Grant (2017), p. 72.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nHer children included:\n* Anne Gordon, who married [[James Stuart, 3rd Earl of Moray]].\n* Elizabeth Gordon, who married [[Alexander Livingston, 2nd Earl of Linlithgow]] in 1611.\n* Mary Gordon, who married [[William Douglas, 1st Marquess of Douglas]].\n* [[George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly]]\n* Jean Gordon, who married [[Claud Hamilton, 2nd Baron Hamilton of Strabane]]\n* John Gordon, [[Viscount of Melgum]].\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n* Ruth Grant, in Elizabeth L. Ewan, Sue Innes, Sian Reynolds, Rose Pipes, ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=Zs6qBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA15&dq=Lady+Henrietta+Stewart+anne+of+denmark&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjF55KmuJThAhXD86YKHVTmDPIQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Lady%20Henrietta%20Stewart%20anne%20of%20denmark&f=false Biographical Dictionary of Scottish Women]'' (Edinburgh, 2018), pp. 411\u2013412.\n* Susan Dunn-Hensley, ''[https://books.google.se/books?id=DaQ5DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA28&dq=Henrietta+huntley+anne+of+denmark&hl=sv&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjCzvnAuZThAhWwyqYKHWI5ClkQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Henrietta%20huntley%20anne%20of%20denmark&f=false Anna of Denmark and Henrietta Maria: Virgins, Witches, and Catholic Queens]''\n* Ruth Grant, 'Friendship, politics and religion: George Gordon, Sixth Earl of Huntly and King James VI, 1581\u20131595', Miles Kerr-Peterson & Steven Reid, ''James VI and Noble Power'' (Abingdon, 2017), pp. 57\u201390.\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stewart, Henrietta}}\n[[Category:1573 births]]\n[[Category:1642 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish ladies-in-waiting]]\n[[Category:Scottish royal favourites]]\n[[Category:Marchionesses]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish women]]\n[[Category:Scottish Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Scottish countesses|#Huntly]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "earl", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henrietta_Stewart"}
